sessionTranslations.title: AI for Java Developers
sessionTranslations.description:
As AI becomes table stakes for enterprise applications, Java developers need to add intelligent features without rewriting their entire tech stack. This comprehensive workshop equips Java developers with practical skills needed to implement powerful AI features in their applications. Through a combination of theory and hands-on coding, you'll learn to build sophisticated AI integrations using familiar Java paradigms.



Starting with foundational concepts, we'll progress to implementing specific AI capabilities including natural language processing, computer vision, and interactive chatbots. The workshop explores advanced techniques such as Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) for enhanced context awareness, and the Model Context Protocol (MCP) for effective AI orchestration. Using Spring AI's powerful abstractions, you'll learn how to write model-agnostic code that works seamlessly with both cloud-based and local AI models, giving you the flexibility to choose the right solution for your specific needs.



Through guided exercises, you'll gain hands-on experience with setting up AI development environments, integrating various AI capabilities into your applications, and building intelligent features that can process text, images, and audio using both local and cloud-based models.

sessionTranslations.title: Finding the bear (so you can poke it)
sessionTranslations.description:
Old people like to say:  "It's hard to carve a bear. Instead, find a piece of wood with a bear in it. Now just cut away everything that isn't the bear". Because it sounds smart without being helpful at all. Every piece of wood has a bear. Even after you make paper out of it. Which is why a better title might be: "Build yer bear (A workshop)"



Writer's block is when you can't "see the bear". It happens to everybody. Your brilliant idea disappears as soon as you try to share. To find/build your bear, we will be writing, moving around, making funny noises (besides "aaaargh"), and stretching metaphors. 



Ages 10+ will get the most benefit, adults are welcome to audit.



Please bring whatever you are most comfortable writing on. (Phone, laptop, tablet, paper, cuniform...) At the bare minimum, participants will have to bear with some truly grizzly ursanine puns. Although they can be polarizing, they are the true sign of koality. Which is actually a marsupial. Panda?

sessionTranslations.title: Threat Modeling with AI – Half-day Workshop
sessionTranslations.description:
This workshop will introduce Security Professionals, Developers, Architects, and Product Managers to integrating AI assistance into their threat modeling workflows. Participants will learn how to leverage AI for diagramming, threat identification, and countermeasure recommendations to speed up threat model analysis.  



To bring these concepts to life, the workshop includes a guided case study on a Digital Wallet / Payment App. Participants will use AI tools to generate a data flow diagram, identify threats using STRIDE, propose mitigations mapped to industry standards, and summarize findings for business stakeholders. This integrated exercise provides an engaging, end-to-end view of how AI can support—but not replace—human judgment in threat modeling. 



While participants should have a working knowledge of Generative AI and LLM concepts and tools (e.g., prompt engineering), no prior experience with threat modeling is required.  



Participants will earn 4 CPE credits for this workshop.

sessionTranslations.title: From Spark to Safety: A Scientific Adventure
sessionTranslations.description: Join us for a thrilling adventure where we transform into "Fire Scientists"! In this hands-on session, we'll dive into the amazing science behind fire, from the tiny spark that starts it all to the firefighters in your community who help keep you safe. We'll become chemists by making a fire "disappear" with a cool experiment, engineers by exploring the gear firefighters wear, and physicists by discovering why we should "stay low and go" during an escape. Get ready to experiment, explore, and become an expert in fire safety!

sessionTranslations.title: Prep Day
Mob / Ensemble Programming Workshop
sessionTranslations.description:
Mob Programming: All the brilliant people working on the same thing, at the same time, in the same place, and on the same computer.



Mob Programming is a cost-effective, collaborative and fun way to get work done together. It's a whole-team approach to development, where coding, designing, testing, and working with the "customer" (partner, Product Owner, User, etc.) is all done as a team.



Participants in this workshop experience a day of learning and doing Mob Programming. We cover the mechanics of how to work together as a Mob as well as the techniques that make this form of development so effective.



We’ll learn how a Mob performs sample project work, including user stories, prioritization, test-driven development, refactoring, and retrospectives.



This workshop provides a hands-on education in the art of mobbing and it's significant benefits for your teams.

sessionTranslations.title: Amazing Algorithms Workshop
sessionTranslations.description:
From genetic algorithms to ant colonies, nature has inspired some of the most powerful problem-solving techniques in computer science. This comprehensive workshop takes you on a journey through three interconnected approaches to algorithmic problem-solving: Dynamic Programming as a foundational technique for optimal decision-making, Genetic Algorithms for evolving solutions to complex optimization problems, and Bio-inspired Algorithms like Firefly and Ant Colony for tackling challenging search spaces.



Through hands-on examples and practical implementations, you'll learn how to identify which algorithm suits different types of problems, implement these techniques in your language of choice, and analyze the tradeoffs of each approach. We'll progress from implementing basic Dynamic Programming solutions to building self-improving systems with Genetic Algorithms and finally explore how nature-inspired algorithms can solve problems that traditional approaches struggle with.



You'll leave with a powerful toolbox of algorithmic techniques, practical implementation knowledge, and the ability to apply these approaches to real-world optimization, search, and decision-making problems in your own systems. Whether you're building resource schedulers, network optimizers, or automated decision engines, these battle-tested algorithms will give you new ways to tackle complex problems elegantly and efficiently.

sessionTranslations.title: Hands-on Terraform and Terragrunt Fundamentals
sessionTranslations.description:
The phrase infrastructure-as-code gets thrown around a lot these days. But getting started might be daunting if you haven’t had free time to learn it on your own and haven’t been thrown into the deep end of the pool to be forced to learn it on the fly.

This workshop is a practical introduction to HashiCorp Terraform and Gruntworks Terragrunt - we won’t focus on theory and history. Instead, we will jump in quickly and build infrastructure in AWS. Then we’ll change it, tear it down, and bring up new cloud resources, all with Terraform and Terragrunt code. Quizzes and exercises abound.

We’ll start with some basic steps to get familiar with the Terraform lifecycle. Then we will expand our environment with variables, outputs, data, loops, and conditionals. We will learn some tools to help us use Terraform safely and securely. We'll finish by adding some flexibility and extra control with Terragrunt.

This is a hands-on workshop. You’ll need a laptop with a browser. We will work in an online environment (AWS Cloud9) to limit prerequisites and setup issues.

sessionTranslations.title: A Swift Start to Building an iOS App
sessionTranslations.description: There have been several exciting new developments in the iOS landscape in the last few years that make building a native iOS app easier than ever. In this precompiler, we'll build an iOS app from scratch using Swift and SwiftUI. We'll reach out to an external API to fetch and display data; we'll make use of common Apple APIs like Alarm Kit, Map Kit, and Event Kit; and we'll set up some simple unit tests with Swift Testing. You'll walk away with a working app to add to your portfolio and solid intro to the skills and patterns common to iOS development.

sessionTranslations.title: Button Masher to Code Master – Unity3D Workshop
sessionTranslations.description: Considered learning how to make video games, but never made the jump? Now is your time to press “space”! No matter your current career (or input device), explore your creative side in Unity and learn the essentials by improving, expanding and customizing a 3D Rollerball game. You’ll start with an intro to the Unity ecosystem before diving into a starter scene, where you’ll power up some simple gameplay features to learn the basics of game development. But that’s just the tutorial level! As you continue to build and customize your game, you will learn about many core video game concepts by working directly on player controllers, special pickups, basic level design, collisions and more. Take this quest to learn and have fun while you do it. You will end this session with a leveled-up knowledge of Unity and game development, propelling you into an open world of possibilities.

sessionTranslations.title: Stop Clicking, Start Scripting: PowerShell for Real People
sessionTranslations.description:
How many times did you copy files to 20 servers last week? Or click through the same dialog boxes to check disk space? Or manually update user accounts one by one?

PowerShell can do all that stuff while you grab coffee.

I'm not here to teach you every PowerShell command ever written. I'm here to show you the 20% that'll solve 80% of your daily headaches. The stuff that actually works in the real world when you're under pressure and need results fast.

What you'll learn:



- How to stop being afraid of the command line

- Five commands that'll handle most of your file and system tasks

- Writing scripts that don't suck (and actually run when you need them to)

- Managing remote machines without remote desktop

- Fixing the same problems I see in every IT shop



This isn't lecture time. We're building things, breaking them, and fixing them. You'll leave with scripts you can use tomorrow.

Come if you manage Windows servers, deal with user accounts, frequently move files around, or want to stop doing the same boring tasks over and over.

Don't come if: you want to become a PowerShell guru in three hours. This is practical stuff for busy people.

Bring a laptop. We're going to make your job easier.

sessionTranslations.title: Mad Scientist Lab V2.0. Sharks to Mars!
sessionTranslations.description:
In years past, we've trained mad scientists by using Raspberry Pi's, electronics, and Python to build sharks with freakin' laser beams in our quest for global domination.  However, we've realized our goal to be overlords of earth were not maniacal enough!  So, this year our sights are much higher.  Using Raspberry Pi Pico microcontrollers, Python, electric motors, 3D printed parts, and your ingenuity, you will construct a rover ready to conquer mars! This vehicle will be capable of traversing rough surfaces like those of the red planet and will be programmable to handle out of this world challenges.  Remember those mechanical sharks with freakin' lasers on their heads?  Well HONEY WE BLEW UP THE SHARKS and will be using those shark parts to transform these rovers into the ULTIMATE MAD SCIENTIST vehicles to fend off any threats you may encounter in this extra-planetary conquest.

Once you've built your functioning JAWS Rover in our lab, if you choose, you will have the opportunity to battle test your vehicle against other rovers to see who's design reigns supreme! Join us in this epic quest and learn to meld software and hardware together to accomplish our goal of bringing Sharks to Mars!



A ticket for this Pre-compiler will entitle you to a kit that includes a Raspberry Pi Pico and the hardware to build a rover that will be yours to keep. You may also bring a lab assistant to help with the assembly and programming (one kit per ticket though!).  Accomplished mad scientists will be in the lab to guide you through the build process.  We will also have stretch goals and challenges for those with previous experience or fast learners.  Come join us for this out of the world fun and learning for all levels!

sessionTranslations.title: Leaving no trace in the great outdoors
sessionTranslations.description:
We've only got one planet, so we need to take care of it! In this session, kids will learn about the principles of Leave No Trace, including both broad concepts ("trash your trash") and specific activities (the "trash timeline", where you discover how long it takes household items to decompose).



Parents: your kids will learn why they shouldn't take home that cool rock they found! (in addition to "because it gets left in our car for three months")



Kids: you'll be able to explain to your parents why it's a moral imperative that you walk through that mud puddle!

sessionTranslations.title: Energize Your Leadership: From Being Stuck to Striving
sessionTranslations.description:
This 4-hour workshop is designed for leaders and professionals who want to understand and overcome the internal barriers that create stress, conflict, and disengagement in their teams. By integrating the core principles of the Energy Leadership framework with the powerful introspection of what’s holding you back, you will learn to identify and dismantle the psychological patterns that trap you and made you feel stuck. You will gain practical tools to intentionally and fundamentally shift your mindset and lead from a place of uplifting influence, and strive.





By the end of this workshop, you will be able to:

• Articulate the seven levels of Energy Leadership and recognize how they show up in daily interactions.

• Uncover and label your personal blockers and see the connection to your energy levels.

• Understand the difference between leading from a reactive state versus an intentional responsive state.

• Develop concrete strategies for challenging your thinking in real-time.

• Practice shifting from an autopilot mindset to a growth mindset, especially in challenging scenarios.



Target Audience

This workshop is ideal for executives, managers, team leads, and any individual contributor who wants to enhance self-awareness and positively impact professional relationships.

sessionTranslations.title: Distilling Intelligence: Hands-On Fine-Tuning using latest AI models
sessionTranslations.description:
How can we make large, powerful AI models smaller, faster, and more efficient—without losing their smarts? Model distillation is the key. In this hands-on workshop, you’ll learn how to take a large “teacher” model and compress its knowledge into a smaller, optimized “student” model that runs faster and costs less to deploy.



We’ll start with the fundamentals: why distillation matters, what problems it solves, and where it’s used in real-world applications. From there, we’ll move into the practical: fine-tuning steps, best practices, and hands-on coding exercises where you’ll implement distillation techniques. Using modern cloud tooling, you’ll explore how to select models, set up a fine-tuning pipeline, and deploy a distilled model into a working application.



By the end, you’ll have the confidence to experiment with teacher–student distillation on your own projects, understand how to adapt it for different scenarios (edge devices, mobile apps, cost-sensitive services), and walk away with working code samples to keep learning after the workshop.



By the end of this workshop, attendees will be able to:

• Explain the significance and use cases of model distillation in modern AI systems.

• Set up a practical workflow for fine-tuning a student model using a larger teacher model.

• Apply best practices for balancing accuracy, performance, and cost in distillation.

• Deploy a distilled model into a real application scenario using modern cloud-based AI tools.



Workshop uses Azure AI Foundry as the orchestration tool, with examples leveraging DeepSeek V3 (teacher) and Phi-4 mini (student) (As of this submission -- Will be updated to latest by actual conference date).

• Hands-on labs will be provided in Jupyter Notebooks; attendees can follow along with cloud credits.

sessionTranslations.title: Lights, Sirens, Action! Discovering EMS
sessionTranslations.description:
In this fun and interactive presentation, kids will learn all about Emergency Medical Services (EMS). We’ll explain what EMS is, what EMTs and paramedics do, and how they help people during emergencies. Children will discover how ambulances work, the types of emergencies EMS responds to and what happens when someone calls 911. Participants will also learn simple first aid skills, such as how to stay calm, when to call for help, and what to do while waiting for EMS to arrive.



Together, we’ll build a basic first aid kit using easy-to-find items, so each child can take home their own kit and feel more prepared. In addition, there will be a hands-on demonstration of real EMS equipment—including stethoscopes, blood pressure cuffs, and backboards—giving kids the opportunity to see how these tools are used and even try them out under supervision.

sessionTranslations.title: SQL Server Query Store Masterclass: From Troubleshooting to Optimization
sessionTranslations.description:
Struggling with query regressions, inconsistent performance, or late-night production calls? Query Store can be your go-to tool for visibility, control, and stability. In this 4-hour, hands-on training, you’ll learn how to use Query Store effectively to diagnose and fix performance issues, prevent regressions, and apply best practices with confidence.



What You’ll Learn:



1. Root Cause Analysis – Find problematic queries, analyze regressions, and interpret Query Store reports.



2. Plan Management – Stabilize performance using plan forcing and automatic plan correction.



3. SQL Server 2022 Enhancements – Explore new features like parameter-sensitive plan optimization and AG replica support.



4. Best Practices & Pitfalls – Configure Query Store correctly, avoid common mistakes, and apply proven troubleshooting tips.



5. Hands-On Labs – Investigate regressions, force plans, configure settings, and practice real-world fixes.



Key Takeaways:



- Practical, repeatable steps for query performance stability.



- Experience with real-world troubleshooting scenarios.



- Confidence to make Query Store your first stop for performance tuning.



This session is demo-driven, hands-on, and focused on providing you with skills that you can apply immediately.

sessionTranslations.title: Beginner’s Method: Rubik’s Cube Basics
sessionTranslations.description: In this session, I will teach kids the beginner’s layer-by-layer method for solving a Rubik’s Cube. Participants will learn the basic terminology, how to solve the first layer, middle layer, and finally the top layer, all while having fun experimenting and racing with their friends. Cubes will be provided for kids who don’t have one, ensuring everyone can participate.

sessionTranslations.title: From Code to Cloud: Building Scalable REST APIs the Right Way
sessionTranslations.description:
Modern applications demand APIs that are fast, reliable, and secure that can scale from day one. This session walks through building REST APIs with Java Spring Boot from the ground up, covering key patterns and best practices for clean, maintainable code. We’ll dive into database design strategies that balance performance and scalability, explore API design principles that avoid common pitfalls, and highlight security and testing considerations that keep systems production-ready. Finally, we’ll deploy everything to the cloud using Infrastructure as Code (IaC), ensuring consistency, repeatability, and speed in releases. The same approach works for launching an MVP quickly and growing it into a full-scale application without costly rewrites. Whether you are building your first API or refining enterprise systems, you will leave with practical guidance for delivering production-grade APIs that scale.



In this session, we will be using SpringBoot, PostgreSQL, and AWS. But the same architecture, designs can be applied to any server frameworks like DotNet, Node, and any databases like SQL Server, MySQL, and more.

sessionTranslations.title: Building a Reusable UI Library with Web Components
sessionTranslations.description:
Web components have been around for a long time (since HTML5), but they haven’t received a lot of attention until recently. Now, tech organizations worldwide are adopting them and finding tremendous efficiency in creating framework-agnostic reusable components to build their Design System component libraries and applications.



In this workshop, we will learn about the important concepts surrounding authoring web components, as well as the technologies used to create, test, and distribute web component libraries for others to utilize.

sessionTranslations.title: Career Conversations: The Missing Skill No One Teaches You
sessionTranslations.description:
Sure, you can spin up a new environment in minutes... but can you ask your manager for that promotion without breaking into a cold sweat?



In this workshop, we’ll treat career conversations like LEGO bricks: small, awkward pieces that don’t look like much on their own, but when snapped into place, can build something remarkable. You’ll practice coding your message so it actually compiles, connecting with the right people (managers, mentors, sponsors, peers, and yourself), and constructing a career that doesn’t topple like a Jenga tower at happy hour.



Come ready to laugh, swap war stories, and maybe even play with some bricks, while learning practical frameworks and practicing to prepare for, navigate, and follow through on the conversations that unlock opportunities, strengthen relationships, and shape your professional journey.

sessionTranslations.title: Demystifying Generative AI
sessionTranslations.description:
Everybody is talking about Generative AI and models that are better than anything else before. What are they really talking about?  



In this hands-on lab, we will discuss about Generative AI in theory and we will try it in practice. After this HOL, you are able to understand what Generative AI is all about and how it can be used.



Hands-on lab will include:

* What is Generative AI?

* What is LLM?

* Interacting with LLM models

* Prompt engineering

* Vectors, embedding models and generating embeddings

* Vector Search with Oracle Database 23ai

* Understanding RAG (Retrieval Augmented Generation)

sessionTranslations.title: Kidz CAD / 3D-Printing level 2: Intro to 3D Modeling lab (Tuesday)
sessionTranslations.description:
This second session is a follow up where we get to make 3D models! 

Children must have a responsible adult present. 



We will work with a fully featured CAD application called Rhino3d and walk through the process of building a basic model from geometric shapes. We will explain the XYZ coordinate system, and what the different views are for. We will also spend some time playing with the transform functions. This session is best for kids with basic skills in measurement, elementary-level geometry, and basic computer skills. The session is probably most appropriate for children over 8 but all are welcome based on the child’s capabilities and ability to enjoy. The goal of the session will be to create a cup model we can print for the student.



Less confident or younger kids are welcome to pair up with parents or siblings and just watch the parent/sibling. Kids that complete the kid’s projects without issue are welcome in the adult walk-through labs as they will be making slightly more advanced models that are different.



PLEASE NOTE: We have a fairly large number of printers in the lab so our kids can possibly print items they make in class. If your child completes a model, we will be able to produce a screen render if desired or we will make our best efforts to print at least one model per student, based on demand.

sessionTranslations.title: Introduction to Electronics part 1 & 2 (Tuesday)
sessionTranslations.description:
Want to get started in electronics but don’t know where to get started? You’ll be shocked how easy it is! Get hands on experience building a few simple circuits and start yer Maker’in!



Kids 10+ welcome with adult supervision. Parts 3 and 4 will cover using Arduino microcontrollers so install Pre-requisites on your laptop for the last section.



Pre-requisites: Arduino IDE (https://www.arduino.cc/en/software)



Additional notes

A paid session is require to get the kit for this class.

sessionTranslations.title: Adult CAD / 3D-Printing level 1: Intro to CAD and 3D printing (Tuesday)
sessionTranslations.description: This session will talk about the exciting world of 3D printing. We will go over exciting trends and happenings in the 3D printing world. We’ll then cover choosing a CAD app and will briefly cover using curated 3D printer object libraries and different CAD apps that might be more appropriate to different types of projects. We will also cover different types of 3D printers as well as the advantages and disadvantages of 3D printing services. After this session you’ll have the starting point on how to make models, where to get them if the model already exists, and where to print them. If you have heard of the exciting world of CAD and 3D printing but have never tried it or would like a basic overview, this session is for you!

sessionTranslations.title: Introduction to Electronics part 3 & 4 (Tuesday)
sessionTranslations.description:
Ever want to build something for your house using a micro controller but didn’t know where to start? This is the session for you!



In this session we will use a Arduino Uno, by far not the smallest micro controller, but perfect for getting started by building a proximity sensor circuit. 



We will start with some basics and build the circuit on a bread board. Then we will solder it onto a prototype board.



Additional notes

A paid session is required to get the kit for this class.

sessionTranslations.title: Kidz CAD / 3D-Printing level 1: Intro to CAD/3D-Printing (Tuesday)
sessionTranslations.description:
This session is targeted for children. All ages of children are welcome based on their ability to enjoy the content being offered! Children must have a responsible adult present. 



We will talk about and watch videos about the exciting world of 3D printing. We will tour the 3D printer lab and look at the printers as well as models made on them We will also go over basics of how to make models and different types of CAD apps including some that are free or more kid friendly as well as looking at more professional apps as well. We’ll also discuss where to get free models and where to print them. This is the basic overview. Kids should start with this session before using the lab or doing the follow-up modeling course.

sessionTranslations.title: Adult CAD / 3D-Printing level 2: Intro to 3D models in Rhino3d (Tuesday)
sessionTranslations.description:
This lab is intended to be a fast-paced technology walk-through of the process of creating a 3D printed object.  We will focus on the process of using CAD to create our model with a NURBS modeler called Rhino3D and will walk through the UI and how Rhino uses basic curves and shapes to create more advanced geometry and create basic models like a goblet, and or a challenge coin. Models can be sent to the 3D printer lab where we will make our best effort to get student models printed!



PLEASE NOTE: High School aged teens or late junior high aged students may also attend adult sessions. Additionally, kids that complete all kid projects in the morning sessions without issue are welcome in this lab as we will be making slightly more advanced models that are different.

sessionTranslations.title: Advanced CAD / 3D-Printing level 3: Making Jewelry (open to Adults and Kidz, Tuesday)
sessionTranslations.description:
Want to make something more advanced than the ones you made in our basic CAD overview? We have some additional options to expand model building skills for those who have been through our previous sessions.



We are offering a deeper dive into the process of making jewelry with CAD and 3D printing. We will go over a brief presentation about various ways of making jewelry from CAD models and then we will transition into a more advanced free form Rhino model-building walk-through session to build a pendant that would work for casting. These models can be printed out on our resin printers.



Open to anyone (kids or adults) who have gone through the regular introductory sessions. PLEASE NOTE this session assumes you have taken the basic overview classes OR are reasonably comfortable working in Rhino3D.



After we get some of the models printed, we plan to offer a tech demo of the process of using Delft Clay to make an impression from the 3D models. 



PLEASE NOTE: This is a session that is likely to have both kid and adult attendees. If your child has attended the introductory class and is looking for a chance to make something more complex, they are welcome in this class. It is likely best for High School aged teens or late junior high aged students, but any kid that has completed the introductory class without issue and is able to follow a slightly faster paced class may also attend.

sessionTranslations.title: Learn to solder (Tuesday)
sessionTranslations.description:
In this year's learn to solder class we will be making a Robot Alarm Clock!



A ticket is required to get the kit that goes with this session.

sessionTranslations.title: Breakfast (Tuesday)
Lunch (Tuesday)
Looney Game-A-Thon (Tue)
sessionTranslations.description: Come play Looney Labs Games with Kristin and Andy Looney all week long in the Zambezi Game Room - and you can win prizes! The Looneys will be using their shiny new Looney Labs Game Tracker to effortlessly track all Looney Labs games played at the event, and award a bunch of prizes to participants. Pick up a badge with your unique Player Code anytime. Thanks for playing Fluxx and other Looney Labs games with us at CodeMash! (Last call on start-of-new-games for Pre-Compiler prizes is 7pm on Wednesday night.)

sessionTranslations.title: [Invitation only] Career Panel for our Volunteers
Dominion: Learn & Play Beginners’ Tournament
sessionTranslations.description:
New this year, CodeMash will offer the opportunity to learn the Dominion game and then immediately compete in a three-game tournament. Winner of the Spiel des Jahres in 2009 and many other awards, Dominion has established itself as a true classic. The game is usually intriguing and fun for information technology types because, as the world’s first deck-building game, you are essentially “programming” your deck to produce the most Victory Points and win. And the replay ability is enormous: with 16 expansions, there are over 88 quintillion starting Kingdom layouts (different game setups) to challenge you.


This event is designed for those new to the game. If you’ve been playing for years, or already own several expansions, or can easily combine Bridge and King’s Court to win the game in one turn, please skip this event. Note: if you played once or twice at your uncle’s birthday party a couple years ago, we’ll let that slide; c’mon and sign up!


There will be a prize for the tournament champion (spoiler alert: it’s a copy of the base Dominion game).


Tickets are free to CodeMash attendees and their families (minimum age 16, and regrettably, unicorns not allowed). Depending on the speed of play, the tournament will last about 2 and a half or 3 hours. There are 8 slots available. Registration required for this session.

sessionTranslations.title: Do you want to build a copilot? Star Wars edition!
sessionTranslations.description:
In this session you will build your first copilot in C# using the new Microsoft.Extensions.AI abstraction, and your choice of LLM from  OpenAI, Azure AI Foundry, or Foundry Local.



We'll look at the fundamentals of a copilot, from chat history to system prompts, creating a simple copilot that imitates your favorite Star Wars character, such as Darth Vader, Yoda, Or Jar Jar Binks (hey, we don't judge).



Then we'll dive into Tools, RAG, and Agents, and see how they can be used to add more knowledge of the Star Wars universe, and more capabilities to your copilot chat.



By the end of this session, you will have a basic understanding of both the architecture of a typical copilot, as well as having built one of your own in C# with Microsoft.Extension.AI and Semantic Kernel.



This session is aimed at developers with a basic understanding of building and debugging C#, and you will need the relevant tooling installed, such as the latest .NET SDK, Visual Studio, Visual Studio Code with the C# extension, or JetBrains Rider.

sessionTranslations.title: Teeny Little Superguys: Build an App Clip and Widget
sessionTranslations.description: App Clips and Widgets are the teeny little superguys of the iOS ecosystem: two powerful, streamlined user experiences that can build your app's audience and bring delight to your users. We'll start with an already fully-featured app and refactor it to be ready for App Clip development; build a stand-alone App Clip that shares resources with the main app; and discuss how to run your App Clip locally as well as how to expose your App Clip to users. We'll also build a dedicated Widget that can live on your users' home screens and expose some app functionality directly to the home screen. We'll discuss what features are appropriate for each experience and how to use them to drive growth and revenue.

sessionTranslations.title: The Gumshoe Protocol
sessionTranslations.description:
It was a dark and stormy night, the kind of night you expect a P0 defect, when the Teams call interrupted my dinner of Cup of Noodles. It was the VP of Customer Success “we have a customer facing problem. We need you and the Gumshoe Team on the case”.



Root cause analysis (RCA) is a critical skill for everyone, however, most professionals have never had the opportunity to identify the root cause of a defect before needing to do so in a critical situation. Effective RCA requires all stakeholders to think critically and use their best judgement on the often limited information available. In this workshop, participants will role-play through a real-life scenario and interact with logs, users, and other stakeholders to figure out the root cause before coming together to brainstorm on how we could have prevented the incident. 



Join the Gumshoe Team of developers, QAs, product professionals, customer support, and project managers to crack the case.

sessionTranslations.title: Reach for the Stars: A Space Explorer Workshop
sessionTranslations.description:
Kids love to look up at the night sky and imagine what is out there. In this workshop, we will become space explorers together, discovering how the Moon changes, how constellations are formed, and what astronauts need to survive in space.



Each child will create a Space Explorer Mission Log filled with their own drawings and discoveries. They will invent a brand-new constellation and build a mini projector to shine their creation onto the walls. Along the way, we will mix science with imagination so that every explorer leaves with a personalized Mission Log, a working star projector, and a spark of curiosity to keep exploring the universe at home.



Learning Objectives

* Explore how and why the Moon looks different throughout the month.

* Use imagination to create original constellations and stories about the stars.

* Build a constellation projector to bring star patterns indoors.

* Design a personal astronaut space suit that solves real space challenges.

sessionTranslations.title: Testing, Evaluating, and Monitoring AI agents using AI Evaluation and OpenTelemetry
sessionTranslations.description:
In this workshop we'll explore on-device techniques for running and evaluating LLMs using open-source tools and ways of monitoring and improving AI solutions using OpenTelemetry, Aspire, and Microsoft.Extensions.AI.Evaluation and .NET.



Prompt engineering can be surprisingly difficult, but AI can help grade the effectiveness of your AI solutions, and metrics over time can tell an interesting story. We'll see how to do this with the built in quality, safety, and NLP evaluators as well as how to write your own evaluator if you need to.



Additionally, minor changes such as tweaking the wording of a prompt, changing a model, or even adding a new tool to an AI system can all have surprising impacts. This is why we'll explore how to write integration tests that take advantage of these evaluation libraries and can be used to detect drift in your overall AI system quality.



Finally, communicating software is hard, but tools like Aspire, OpenTelemetry, and AI Evaluation reporting can help you quickly build visuals to share with other team members to show how your system is trending over time.



By the time we're done, you'll have more tools at your disposal to build and consistently deliver high quality LLM solutions.

sessionTranslations.title: LLMs Under the Hood
sessionTranslations.description:
Large Language Models (LLMs) have revolutionized the field of natural language processing, enabling machines to generate human-like text with remarkable coherence.



In this comprehensive workshop, we'll take a deep technical journey through the transformative world of Large Language Models (LLMs), exploring three crucial aspects that are revolutionizing software development: the Transformer architecture, embeddings, and Retrieval Augmented Generation (RAG).



We begin by unraveling the intricate architecture of transformer models, examining the fundamental mechanisms that enable these tools to understand and generate human-like text. From embedding layers to attention mechanisms, you'll gain a thorough understanding of how these models process and predict tokens. This foundation sets the stage for understanding both the capabilities and limitations of LLMs in practical applications.



Building on this knowledge, we'll dive into the mathematical foundations of embeddings, one of the most powerful yet misunderstood tools in the LLM ecosystem. You'll learn how to leverage various comparison techniques like Cosine similarity and clustering to create sophisticated applications that go beyond basic chat interfaces. Through hands-on examples, you'll discover how to transform raw text into meaningful vector representations that capture semantic relationships.



The workshop culminates with an in-depth exploration of RAG systems, demonstrating how to combine the pre-trained knowledge of LLMs with your own data sources. Using C# and the Microsoft OpenAI Client, we'll implement practical RAG solutions that address real business challenges. You'll learn strategies for managing request complexity, ensuring retrieval accuracy, handling model biases, and validating response authenticity.



By the end of this workshop, you'll possess a comprehensive understanding of LLM technology, from theoretical foundations to practical implementation. Whether you're building content generation systems, or information retrieval solutions, you'll be equipped with the knowledge and tools to harness these technologies responsibly and effectively in your applications.

sessionTranslations.title: Building and Deploying a .NET 10 App to Azure Using Bicep, and GitHub Actions
sessionTranslations.description:
In this workshop, we'll cover the soup to nuts on deploying an ASP.NET Core 10 API to Azure App Service using Bicep and GitHub Actions. 



Lots of times this kind of stuff gets set up once and then you never touch it for awhile. This usually leads to one (or all) of these outcomes:

- you weren't the one to set it up so you have no clue how it works

- this knowledge gets forgotten

- it isn't done often so you don't know the best way to do it



In this session, we'll start from the beginning sprinkling in some .NET concepts, Azure concepts, and GitHub Actions concepts. We'll cover all of these topics:

- Using Bicep to provision the infrastructure

- Using GitHub Actions to deploy the app

- Learning how App Service works

- Configuring Zero Downtime Deployments with Deployment Slots



We'll mix in presentation with hands-on labs to get you up and productive with the full stack of building and maintaining an ASP.NET Core API.



If you're interested in learning how any of these technologies work, you don't want to miss this workshop.

sessionTranslations.title: What to expect when you are expected to Game Master
sessionTranslations.description:
You bought the books and read the rules. You've invited your friends and filled the chip bowls. You are about to transport the group into a magical world and fill their lives with adventure! Now what?



In this session we will cover everything you need to know to get your tabletop role-playing game up and running and set up for long term success, including:



- How to run a successful "Session 0"

- How to prep without over-prepping

- How to use AI to create a more vibrant and lifelike world

- Common pitfalls of first time GM's and how to avoid them

- Different flavors of role-playing games



The hobby of tabletop role-playing games is exploding, and every group needs a confident Game Master. This session is filled with practical advice that will set you up for success!

sessionTranslations.title: Scaling from 1 to Infinity: Building Simpler Distributed Applications w/ the Actor Model
sessionTranslations.description:
If you are a software developer working on distributed systems and looking for a way to simplify scalability and concurrency, this session is for you. Whether you’re a seasoned developer aiming to streamline complex code or a system architect focused on designing fault-tolerant applications, this focused exploration into the Actor Model will provide the insights you need. We’ll dive into how the Actor Model, a time-tested programming paradigm, can revolutionize your approach to building distributed systems. Despite being around for decades, the Actor Model remains an under-appreciated gem in systems development, offering a straightforward way to manage concurrency, scale applications, and handle failure gracefully.



During the session you can expect:



* An Introduction to the Actor Model: Understand the core concepts of the Actor Model and how it simplifies the complexity of distributed programming by making concurrency manageable and reducing code complexity.

* Hands-On Application Development: We’ll build a sample application using Akka, showcasing the key principles of the Actor Model in action.

* Learning Fault Tolerance with Actors: Discover how the Actor Model’s built-in fault tolerance mechanisms allow applications to fail gracefully and recover quickly, making your systems more resilient.

* Scaling Made Simple: Learn how to deploy your Akka-based application and how it can scale elastically, leveraging the Actor Model’s location transparency to simplify deployment across various network boundaries.



You will walk away from this precompiler with the knowledge and confidence to start building distributed applications that can scale from one user to millions, without the typical headaches (and often re-writes) of distributed systems. You’ll be equipped to leverage the Actor Model in your own projects, enabling you to build applications that are not only scalable and fault-tolerant but also easier to maintain and deploy—whether your app serves a trickle of users or a hoard.

sessionTranslations.title: [KidzMash] Great Ball Contraption Workshop
sessionTranslations.description: What do you get if you take LEGO soccer balls, a simple set of instructions, a provided LEGO model kit, and put it all together? A Rube Goldberg machine entirely from LEGO! Together we will build modules for a Great Ball Contraption and then line them all up to pass along the soccer balls. Let's set the first KidzMash GBC record together, while learning and playing with LEGO.

sessionTranslations.title: Unlocking Quantum Computing: A Hands-On Mystery
sessionTranslations.description:
Dr. Codewell Mashfield has vanished from his quantum research lab, leaving behind only encrypted files, scattered notes, and a trail of cryptic code. 



In this hands-on mystery workshop, you’ll take on the role of an investigator, using Python and Qiskit to follow his quantum-encrypted trail. Each puzzle introduces a real quantum computing concept, superposition, interference, entanglement, and more, all wrapped in an interactive, beginner-friendly storyline. No prior experience is required. Just bring your laptop, a little Python, and a sense of curiosity. 



By the end, you’ll have pieced together the clues and gained enough quantum perspective to talk with confidence and recognize its role in tomorrow’s development.

sessionTranslations.title: Artemis (Tues 7pm)
Artemis (Tues 8pm)
Artemis (Tues 9pm)
Speak Geek: Unlocking Communication Superpowers
sessionTranslations.description: As a developer, you speak in code, but what happens when you need to translate that into “human”? Whether you’re chatting with UX folks, wrangling with management, or just trying to explain your latest bug hunt to someone outside tech, communication is a superpower you can actually level up. In this hands-on workshop, we’ll break down the quirks of dev-to-dev, dev-to-UX, and dev-to-everyone-else conversations. We’ll play games inspired by “Poetry for Neanderthals” and “Just One,” and even challenge you to meme your message—no words allowed! Come ready to laugh, learn, and unlock your inner communication hero. Learn to challenge ambiguous conversation into actionable thoughts/items. You’ll leave with practical tools and a fresh perspective to help your team work (and talk) better, together.

sessionTranslations.title: Build Your Own Paper Computer
sessionTranslations.description:
When I was in 6th grade, my math teacher, Mr. Fred Matt, handed us stacks of paper and showed us how to build a “paper computer.” It wasn’t fast, and it definitely wasn’t digital, but it worked. More importantly, it helped me—and has continued to help me throughout my career—finally see how computers really operate, step by step.



In this hands-on workshop, you’ll build your own paper computer from scratch. Together we’ll run a few programs so you can see how the pieces fit together, and then you’ll design your own programs to test your paper machine. No coding or prior knowledge required—just curiosity and a sense of fun. By the end, you’ll not only have a working paper computer to take home, but also a whole new way of understanding how the devices around us actually think—an understanding that can stick with you for life.

sessionTranslations.title: Code Your Own LEGO World
sessionTranslations.description:
Coding. Blocks. What do they have in common? Building comes from following some sort of instruction, building one piece at a time. But what if coding didn’t have to feel intimidating, and instead just as fun as snapping blocks together? 



In this session, kids will explore the logic of coding through LEGO-style thinking. We’ll act out a “coding game” where the audience gives step-by-step instructions to build a small LEGO mode. Along the way, you’ll practice the same skills real programmers use: writing algorithms, fixing mistakes, and getting creative with your builds.

sessionTranslations.title: Hands-On AI Vision at the Edge: Building Smarter IoT Devices
sessionTranslations.description:
Cameras are everywhere, but turning raw video into useful insights at the edge is still a major challenge. In this hands-on workshop, you’ll learn how to build intelligent IoT devices that can “see” the world using AI vision models running locally on low-cost hardware. Together, we’ll wire up an edge device, deploy a computer vision model, and stream meaningful telemetry to the cloud for real-time analysis.



Whether you’re new to IoT or looking to level up your edge AI skills, you’ll leave with practical experience in connecting sensors, optimizing models for constrained devices, and designing systems that balance local intelligence with cloud-scale services. By the end of the session, you’ll have built your own vision-enabled IoT prototype—and gained the skills to apply these patterns to your own projects.

sessionTranslations.title: Snack Time: EventStorming with Snack-Inspired Systems
sessionTranslations.description: Ever wondered how a vending machine really works? This 4-hour workshop dives into Event Storming and how it can improve your system design and coding experiences, using a vending machine as our case study. We’ll uncover hidden bottlenecks, streamline workflows, and build a clearer understanding of any system - from snack machines to software. Through engaging, hands-on Event Storming exercises, participants will collaboratively map out every step, revealing opportunities for improvement and building a more ‘constructible’ solution. It's about getting to the heart of the matter, just like understanding how a vending machine delivers your favorite treat. Join us for an interactive session on how EventStorming can be used for exploratory conversations as well as for designing better systems with better requirements and a shared understanding.

sessionTranslations.title: Azure Cosmos DB for Developers: From Basics to AI
sessionTranslations.description:
This workshop is perfect for any developer eager to explore how to integrate Azure Cosmos DB into their applications! We’ll dive into the ins and outs of Azure Cosmos DB, helping you gain a thorough understanding of its architecture, features, and handy tools. We’ll also cover essential concepts like partitioning and data modeling for distributed NoSQL databases, making sure you feel confident in working with this powerful technology.



The workshop will include an in-depth look at all the database services offered by Azure Cosmos DB, with a primary focus on the SQL API. We will utilize the Azure Cosmos DB Emulator as much as possible, so participants may not need an Azure subscription for most of the workshop. Additionally, attendees will learn how to use the Azure Cosmos DB Data Migration Tool to migrate data from various sources into Azure Cosmos DB.



Azure Cosmos DB provides a range of AI capabilities via Azure AI Foundry. In the workshop's concluding section, participants will explore AI features and vector data options available in Azure Cosmos DB.



Participants are welcome to join the workshop with or without their computer, as there will be valuable learning opportunities regardless of whether a computer is used.

sessionTranslations.title: Coding Effectively with AI
sessionTranslations.description: It seems everyone is coding with AI assistance these days. But how do we do so effectively? And how do we pick an approach? In this workshop, we'll explore picking an editor vs using a CLI, choosing models, config techniques for optimizing outputs, creating custom agents, code review workflows, using and configuring MCP servers, spec driven development, context management, prompting techniques, and more. We'll alternate between concepts and coding so you can try these techniques in real-time. Attendees will walk away with a variety of new ideas to consider and a mental model for how to choose between them.

sessionTranslations.title: Elevating Trust: Tools for Leaders and Teams
sessionTranslations.description: Trust is the foundation of every successful relationship personally, professionally, and organizationally. Yet, it’s often taken for granted until it’s broken. In this interactive workshop, we’ll explore what it truly means to build and sustain trust in today’s fast paced, interconnected world. You’ll learn practical strategies to strengthen self-trust, deepen trust in relationships, and contribute to cultures where trust accelerates results. Together, we’ll uncover the hidden “trust taxes” of low-trust environments, the dividends of high trust, and how trust shapes everything from collaboration to innovation. Through engaging exercises and discussions, you’ll leave equipped with actionable tools to build trust that inspires confidence, enhances credibility, and drives meaningful outcomes.

sessionTranslations.title: REALLY Old School Games
sessionTranslations.description: How did kids entertain themselves before video games, YouTube, and plastic toys?   Take a look back in time at games children played in early America - games of the Indigenous people, those that traveled on the Mayflower and kids during the Colonial Period.  Learn games like 3 Men’s Morris, marble & stone games, hoop and stick games and more…and then make and take some of these games so you can practice at home!

sessionTranslations.title: Modern UX Without JavaScript Madness (Workshop)
sessionTranslations.description: Say goodbye to bloated frontends and client-side chaos. In this workshop, you'll discover how htmx and ASP.NET Core enable you to build fast, modern, and interactive web apps without relying on a full SPA framework. Through hands-on labs and real-world examples, you’ll learn to enhance Razor Pages and MVC with htmx-powered features such as real-time validation, partial updates, dynamic forms, and smooth UX patterns, all while keeping the logic on the server where it belongs. This is not just a tooling demo; it’s a new mindset for building user interfaces: one that prioritizes simplicity, performance, and developer happiness.

sessionTranslations.title: Building Trust and Breaking Barriers (with LEGO!)
sessionTranslations.description:
LEGO(R) sets are fun to build, but who has ever attempted to build a set without looking at the instructions? In this workshop, attendees will form teams and attempt to build a LEGO(R) set without instructions. Through a series of iterative exercises that provide more product details, the teams will attempt to build & test their product as close to the instructions as possible without peeking.



Each group will learn different approaches to collaborate on product development and testing during the meeting to build a set according to a customer's needs. The workshop will highlight the gap between what we set out to build & the finished product as well as the gap between what our customers expect & the finished product. Our goal as a group will be to refine our techniques so we deliver a product on-time & on-budget that customers will love.

sessionTranslations.title: Introduction to Electronics part 3 & 4 (Wednesday)
sessionTranslations.description:
Ever want to build something for your house using a micro controller but didn’t know where to start? This is the session for you!



In this session we will use a Arduino Uno, by far not the smallest micro controller, but perfect for getting started by building a proximity sensor circuit. 



We will start with some basics and build the circuit on a bread board. Then we will solder it onto a prototype board.



Additional notes

A paid session is required to get the kit for this class.

sessionTranslations.title: Kidz CAD / 3D-Printing level 1: Intro to CAD/3D-Printing (Wednesday)
sessionTranslations.description:
This session is targeted for children. All ages of children are welcome based on their ability to enjoy the content being offered! Children must have a responsible adult present. 



We will talk about and watch videos about the exciting world of 3D printing. We will tour the 3D printer lab and look at the printers as well as models made on them We will also go over basics of how to make models and different types of CAD apps including some that are free or more kid friendly as well as looking at more professional apps as well. We’ll also discuss where to get free models and where to print them. This is the basic overview. Kids should start with this session before using the lab or doing the follow-up modeling course.

sessionTranslations.title: Introduction to Electronics part 1 & 2 (Wednesday)
sessionTranslations.description:
Want to get started in electronics but don’t know where to get started? You’ll be shocked how easy it is! Get hands on experience building a few simple circuits and start yer Maker’in!



Kids 10+ welcome with adult supervision. Parts 3 and 4 will cover using Arduino microcontrollers so install Pre-requisites on your laptop for the last section.



Pre-requisites: Arduino IDE (https://www.arduino.cc/en/software)



Additional notes

A paid session is require to get the kit for this class.

sessionTranslations.title: Kidz CAD / 3D-Printing level 2: Intro to 3D Modeling lab (Wednesday)
sessionTranslations.description:
This second session is a follow up where we get to make 3D models! 

Children must have a responsible adult present.



We will work with a fully featured CAD application called Rhino3d and walk through the process of building a basic model from geometric shapes. We will explain the XYZ coordinate system, and what the different views are for. We will also spend some time playing with the transform functions. This session is best for kids with basic skills in measurement, elementary-level geometry, and basic computer skills. The session is probably most appropriate for children over 8 but all are welcome based on the child’s capabilities and ability to enjoy. The goal of the session will be to create a cup model we can print for the student.



Less confident or younger kids are welcome to pair up with parents or siblings and just watch the parent/sibling. Kids that complete the kid’s projects without issue are welcome in the adult walk-through labs as they will be making slightly more advanced models that are different.



PLEASE NOTE: We have a fairly large number of printers in the lab so our kids can possibly print items they make in class. If your child completes a model, we will be able to produce a screen render if desired or we will make our best efforts to print at least one model per student, based on demand.

sessionTranslations.title: Adult CAD / 3D-Printing level 1: Intro to CAD and 3D printing (Wednesday)
sessionTranslations.description: This session will talk about the exciting world of 3D printing. We will go over exciting trends and happenings in the 3D printing world. We’ll then cover choosing a CAD app and will briefly cover using curated 3D printer object libraries and different CAD apps that might be more appropriate to different types of projects. We will also cover different types of 3D printers as well as the advantages and disadvantages of 3D printing services. After this session you’ll have the starting point on how to make models, where to get them if the model already exists, and where to print them. If you have heard of the exciting world of CAD and 3D printing but have never tried it or would like a basic overview, this session is for you!

sessionTranslations.title: Adult CAD / 3D-Printing level 2: Intro to 3D models in Rhino3d (Wednesday)
sessionTranslations.description:
This lab is intended to be a fast-paced technology walk-through of the process of creating a 3D printed object.  We will focus on the process of using CAD to create our model with a NURBS modeler called Rhino3D and will walk through the UI and how Rhino uses basic curves and shapes to create more advanced geometry and create basic models like a goblet, and or a challenge coin. Models can be sent to the 3D printer lab where we will make our best effort to get student models printed!



PLEASE NOTE: High School aged teens or late junior high aged students may also attend adult sessions. Additionally, kids that complete all kid projects in the morning sessions without issue are welcome in this lab as we will be making slightly more advanced models that are different.

sessionTranslations.title: Advanced CAD / 3D-Printing level 3: Making a Race Car (open to Adults and Kidz, Wednesday)
sessionTranslations.description:
Want to make something more advanced than the ones you made in our basic CAD overview? We have some additional options to expand model building skills for those who have been through our previous sessions.



This session the goal will be to build a raceable “matchbox/hot wheels scaled” 3d-printed race car. We will be using a variety of model techniques to produce a model car that resembles a real race car and then print it out on the lab’s advanced resin printers. While this session will repeat, the idea will be that attendees are welcome to come to both race league sessions and make different cars or continue working on tuning the model into a super car!



Open to anyone (kids or adults) who have gone through the regular introductory sessions. PLEASE NOTE this session assumes you have taken the basic overview classes OR are reasonably comfortable working in Rhino3D.



We will have some track pieces at the lab to test and possibly race the cars once we get them built! 



PLEASE NOTE: This is a session that is likely to have both kid and adult attendees. If your child has attended the introductory class and is looking for a chance to make something more complex, they are welcome in this class. It is likely best for High School aged teens or late junior high aged students, but any kid that has completed the introductory class without issue and is able to follow a slightly faster paced class may also attend.

sessionTranslations.title: Breakfast (Wednesday)
Lunch (Wednesday)
Learn to solder (Wednesday)
sessionTranslations.description:
In this year's learn to solder class we will be making a Robot Alarm Clock!



A ticket is required to get the kit that goes with this session.

sessionTranslations.title: IaC Forged in Code: ARM/Bicep vs Terraform vs Pulumi
sessionTranslations.description: Infrastructure as Code (IaC) is a powerful way to automate the deployment of your Azure infrastructure. With IaC, you can define your infrastructure in code, and use that code to deploy and manage your resources. In this session, we will explore the different ways to use IaC in Azure, including Azure Resource Manager (ARM) templates, Microsoft's Bicep language processor, and popular open-source tools like Terraform and Pulumi. We'll also compare the pros and cons of each approach, and discuss when it's best to use each one. Whether you're new to IaC or a seasoned veteran, this session will provide you with the knowledge you need to take your cloud deployments to the next level.

sessionTranslations.title: The Fewer Environments the Better: Lean DevOps Strategies
sessionTranslations.description: Many companies have a half-dozen long-lived environments, complex branching strategies, shared DB instances, many related repositories, insufficient automated tests, and risky, large, infrequent releases. What's the path to incremental improvement? In this session, we'll explore strategies for simplifying DevOps. We'll explore feature flags, testing in prod, ephemeral environments, canary releases, static datasets, per-developer databases, pre-merge vs post-merge QA, and more. After this session, you'll have a list of ideas for streamlining your environments and workflows.

sessionTranslations.title: Leveraging Generative AI for Faster, Smarter Design
sessionTranslations.description:
Prototyping is essential for bringing ideas to life, but what if you could accelerate the process without sacrificing creativity? Generative AI is transforming the way designers and product teams build and test concepts, streamlining workflows and unlocking new possibilities.



In this session, I’ll explore how generative AI can enhance the prototyping process—from generating wireframes and UI elements to rapidly iterating on design ideas. I’ll share real-world examples, practical tools, and strategies for integrating AI into your workflow while maintaining human creativity and control. Whether you're a UX designer, product manager, or developer, you'll leave with actionable insights on how to harness AI for faster, smarter, and more innovative prototyping.

sessionTranslations.title: Lightning Talks
Welcome Reception
Rave
Create multi-platform apps with .NET MAUI and the MAUI Community Toolkit
sessionTranslations.description:
Start your cross-platform app development journey with C# and .NET MAUI. .NET developers can build apps for iOS, Android, macOS, and Windows with a single codebase. In this session, we'll explore multiple techniques to create apps quickly with .NET MAUI:



- Build an app quickly with XAML, C#, and VS Code

- Use the controls, extensions, behaviors, and more from the .NET MAUI Community Toolkit

- Follow the Model-View-ViewModel (MVVM) pattern and reduce boilerplate code with the MVVM Toolkit

- Create MAUI apps without any XAML by leveraging C# Markup

- Reuse your web styles and bring your CSS into .NET MAUI projects

- Access device-specific platform features without writing platform-specific code

- Learn which tools are available to write, build and debug your apps on Windows and macOS



By the end of this session, you'll have some new tools in your cross-platform toolbelt to get your apps into users' hands faster on every platform.

sessionTranslations.title: Ditch your JavaScript for CSS!
sessionTranslations.description:
Speed is critical in Web Design. There are things done daily on websites that can be managed in CSS as easily as JavaScript—simply faster. Over the years, I have encountered dozens of these patterns.



Let’s look at both sides of these code examples and discuss their pros and cons. Can we (or should we) ditch JavaScript for CSS?

sessionTranslations.title: [CANCELLED] Behind the Lazy Curtain: What Your Framework Is Really Doing
sessionTranslations.description:
As web apps scale and user expectations rise, the race to faster load times is more critical than ever. Lazy loading has become the go-to strategy to speed up perceived performance—but not all lazy loading is created equal. Under the hood, each major frontend framework tackles this challenge differently, with varying levels of control, complexity, and tradeoffs.



This workshop dives into how React, Angular, and Vue implement lazy loading—revealing not just what works, but why it works (or doesn’t) in real-world scenarios. We'll break down the internals behind code splitting, route-based loading, dynamic imports, and module boundaries, showing how these design choices shape everything from time-to-interactive to dev experience and long-term scalability.



You’ll learn how code splitting, lazy loading, and parallel builds aren’t just nice-to-haves—they’re performance multipliers hiding in plain sight and you'll get hands-on with each. We’ll dive into practical strategies to restructure your app for speed, uncover surprising bottlenecks, and show how small architectural shifts can yield surprising gains for both users and developers. For those chasing faster load times and shorter feedback loops, this talk is your blueprint.



Whether you're picking a new frontend stack or trying to squeeze every millisecond out of your current one, this session will help you make smarter, framework-aware architectural decisions based on actual data.

sessionTranslations.title: #gitPanic - Restoring Lost Work
sessionTranslations.description: Have you ever opened a PR and suddenly realized some of your or your coworker's work is missing? Maybe you've been too afraid to run a git command just in case you mess it up. This talk will cover how to avoid that oh so familiar #gitPanic. Learn how to stop commands that are going horribly wrong, ways to find the refs you need to get your work back, and a couple ways to save a back up copy before you even start.

sessionTranslations.title: Git Configuration secrets THEY don't want you to know about
sessionTranslations.description:
In 2021 the Git core developers were asked to reset their config settings to see what working on Git "Out of the Box" was really like. They were then challenged to come up with the top settings that they really wanted to change. What came from that exercise was a list of 9 settings that the core development team mostly unanimously agreed should be the defaults.



Attendees will leave this session with the following take ways:



* How to configure Git so it is more ergonomic and pleasant to work with

* How Git settings may change depending on our workflow

* A deeper understanding of the internals of Git

sessionTranslations.title: Diet Docker: Crafting lightweight containers with multi-stage builds
sessionTranslations.description:
Building containerized applications should not mean bloated images and unnecessary dependencies. Modern software demands fast developer experience and fast deployments, but oversized images can slow down your builds at the critical moments of development and deployment. Multi-stage builds with Docker are a powerful method for streamlining your workflows.



In this session, we will break down how to craft an efficient multi-stage Dockerfile tailored for a fast inner loop and secure production image. We will compile, test, and publish our .NET application within a single Dockerfile while ensuring the final image contains only essential artifacts for production. You’ll learn the basics of Dockerfiles, how to utilize stages, optimize caching, and refine build layers to keep your Docker builds fast. Whether you are looking to accelerate your inner loop, improve application security, or better understand containers, you’ll leave equipped with essential knowledge and practices for cloud-native development.

sessionTranslations.title: Building Accessible Components with Razor
sessionTranslations.description: Creating robust experiences using C# and .NET is pretty great if you are a back-end developer, but what if your power lies in the front end? Were you ever tasked to build in accessibility, but the only catch was it had to be supported by C# developers? The power of ASP.NET Core and C# 7 far exceeds the Microsoft technologies of the past, but it is still lacking in terms of building in solutions for accessibility. Razor syntax is the bridge between the back-end C# code and front-end HTML for creating beautiful user interfaces, that can also be accessibility-compliant. In this talk, I will briefly go through an intro to accessibility, Razor syntax, and build a standard form out of Razor syntax that is functional as well as accessible for users with disabilities.

sessionTranslations.title: htmx - Web Development Simplified
sessionTranslations.description:
This talk describes building web applications focused on hypermedia, an approach that differs significantly from the SPA frameworks popular today such as React and Angular.



Today, web apps typically use client-side JavaScript code to send HTTP requests to server endpoints that query/update databases and return JSON data. The client code then transforms JSON into an HTML presentation.



This is not what Roy Fielding had in mind when he wrote his famous dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" that gave birth to REST.



HTMX is a small client-side JavaScript library that adds support for new HTML attributes. These enable responding to specific interactions (ex. click) with any HTML element by sending an HTTP request using any verb. The response must contain HTML. Rather than performing a complete page refresh, the returned HTML replaces an existing DOM element or is inserted relative to one.



This approach removes the need to serialize data to JSON on the server, parse JSON on the client, and convert it to HTML. It also simplifies state management because all state can reside only on the server.



The server can be implemented using any programming language and server framework. While HTMX itself is implemented in JavaScript, HTMX enables writing complete web applications without authoring any JavaScript code.



Topics covered will include:



- Introduction to htmx

- Choosing a tech stack

- Example htmx app

- Pros and cons

- Frequently used htmx attributes

- Out-of-band swaps

- Input validation

- Lazy loading

- Active search

- Infinite scroll

- Alpine

- Resources
