sessionTranslations.title: Make Your Resume Work Harder Than You Do
sessionTranslations.description:
As a hiring manager on the hunt for Senior Developers, I’ve reviewed hundreds—maybe thousands—of resumes. Some are crisp, clear, and make me want to schedule an interview before I finish reading. Others? Let’s just say they require a decoder ring, a magnifying glass, and a strong cup of coffee.

The truth is: your resume is your first impression, and if it makes my job easier, you’re already ahead of the game. If it makes me squint, scroll, or sigh… well, you might be silently voted off the island.

In this session, we’ll break down what separates the “easy yes” resumes from the ones that get buried in the maybe pile. We’ll talk about what hiring managers actually look for, what signals seniority, and how to avoid the most common resume missteps. Expect real examples, candid advice, and maybe a few resume horror stories (names changed to protect the guilty).

Whether you’re polishing your own resume or coaching others, this conversation will help you write like someone who knows their worth—and makes it easy for others to see it too.

sessionTranslations.title: Pair Programming Interviews: The Most Awkward First Date You’ll Ever Love
sessionTranslations.description:
Let’s be honest: pair programming interviews can feel like a weird mix of speed dating, live coding, and performance art. You’re trying to impress, collaborate, communicate, and not accidentally delete the main branch—all while someone silently judges your keyboard shortcuts.

In this talk, we’ll explore how to make pair programming interviews less awkward and more effective—for both interviewers and candidates. We’ll cover what great pairing looks like under pressure, how to spot real senior-level signals (hint: it’s not just who types), and how to create an environment that reveals technical depth and team fit.

Expect candid stories, practical tips, and a few laughs as we unpack the good, the bad, and the “did they really Google that?” moments from real-world pairing interviews. Whether you’re hiring or being hired, you’ll walk away with strategies to make pairing interviews feel less like a test—and more like the beginning of a great working relationship.

sessionTranslations.title: MQTT + Ollama = Building Home Automation That Actually Works (And Doesn't Spy on You)
sessionTranslations.description:
Tired of smart home devices that need the internet to turn on a light bulb? Fed up with voice assistants that mishear "dim the bedroom" as "order three tons of cat food"? This session explores how to create a truly intelligent home automation system using Ollama for local AI processing and MQTT for reliable device communication. We'll examine how a custom MCP (Model Context Protocol) server translates natural language commands into MQTT messages, letting you control Z-Wave devices, smart switches, and sensors through conversational AI that runs entirely on your local network. Unlike corporate voice assistants that maintain corporate politeness, your local AI can have personality – imagine an assistant that responds to "turn off all the lights" with "Finally going to bed at a reasonable hour? Impressive." or sarcastically comments when you ask it to turn the heat up for the third time today.



We'll explore how this architecture bridges AI understanding and IoT device control, turning "make the living room cozy for movie night" into precise MQTT commands thatcoordinate multiple devices. The session covers integration patterns with popular platforms like Home Assistant and Z-Wave JS, examines Home Assistant's remarkable progress through their Year of Voice initiative (including their recent achievements in local voice processing), and demonstrates how structured prompting creates reliable device control while maintaining the personality you actually want in your home. No cloud dependencies, no monthly subscriptions, and definitely no corporate eavesdropping on your late-night snack requests – just a working example of how local AI can make your smart home both intelligent and entertaining.

sessionTranslations.title: Vector Databases and Embeddings Demystified
sessionTranslations.description:
Ever wonder how Netflix knows you'll love that obscure documentary about penguins, or how Google Photos finds every picture of your dog even though you never tagged them? The secret sauce is vector embeddings and similarity search – technologies that convert complex data (text, images, audio) into high-dimensional numerical representations that capture semantic meaning. While traditional databases excel at exact matches ("find user ID 12345"), vector databases revolutionize "find similar" queries by measuring relationships between these numerical vectors using techniques like cosine similarity. This session demystifies the math and technology behind the AI-powered search and recommendation systems you use every day.



You'll discover how companies transform words into vectors where "king" - "man" + "woman" actually equals "queen" in mathematical space, explore the architecture behind popular vector databases like Pinecone and see live demonstrations of building semantic search systems. We'll cover real-world applications from RAG-powered chatbots to fraud detection, show you how to implement document similarity search in 20 lines of Python, and discuss the practical considerations of scaling vector systems to billions of embeddings. Whether you're building recommendation engines, semantic search, or AI-powered applications, this session provides the foundational knowledge to leverage vector databases effectively in your projects.

sessionTranslations.title: Dev Containers. What are they and why do you need them?
sessionTranslations.description:
You're onboarding a new team member, or your team recently inherited a project that uses a different SDK/framework version than your current project uses. What do you do?  Install the old SDK/framework versions? Can they even be installed at the same time on the same machine?  What if I told you there was a way to accomplish this with little to no effort on your part?  Well, with Visual Studio Code, Docker, and the Dev Containers extension, you can.  Dev containers can help you easily on-board new people to your projects, allow for cleaner machines with greater support for multiple SDKs/Framework, and be able to develop/debug/run your solution from anywhere without Visual Studio Code. Oh, and put an end to "It works on my machine"



In this talk, I’ll walk through how you can set up a dev container to support your application development, without installing the SDK/framework on your machine. I’ll show you how to get started and how you can solve the age-old problem of “It works on my machine!”.  As a bonus, if your code is hosted on GitHub, I’ll show you how you can run/edit/debug your project right from GitHub.com without Visual Studio Code on your machine.

sessionTranslations.title: Conquering Events with Streaming Analytics
sessionTranslations.description:
Step into the world of stream processing, where events arrive sporadically and timing matters.



This talk explores managing the journey and lifetime of an events during stream processing. We will discuss data events from ingestion to output and examine what happens along the way.



Using a movie theater metaphor, we will explain key ideas like time windows, late arrivals, and dead letter queues. The talk connects high-level concepts to practical implementation notes. You will leave with a clear and useful mental model for working with real-time data.

sessionTranslations.title: Think like a Computer
sessionTranslations.description: Ever wondered how computers or their programs work? In this session we'll explore this together by having individual kids represent different parts of a computer program and see how all the little bits and pieces come together to build fun and meaningful programs. We'll cover simple programs and variables, loops and conditional logic, and more fun concepts like AI and games! We'll also learn some fun ways of exploring these concepts in more depth after KidzMash is over through games, hands-on-activities, and more!

sessionTranslations.title: A Bug's Life
sessionTranslations.description:
**tl;dr:**

A beginner-friendly talk that traces a production bug from discovery back to inception, asking: what else needs a patch beyond code?



**The Bug:**

The talk opens with the support pager alerting the team to an outage in a low-latency, real-time trading system.

With every second of downtime resulting in revenue loss, it's all hands on deck for the site reliability team, dev team, data team, and product owners. 

We witness the scrambling for locating the culprit commits in a distributed system, how hotfixes are pushed with heroic efforts.

After the fire, we cut to the "blameless" postmortem, where the question of what else needs a patch beyond changing lines of code.



**Takeaways for the audience:**

Modern software deployments are complex, dynamic ecosystems - ideal breeding grounds for bugs.  

While vibe coding and agentic code generation has accelerated the volume and velocity of code pushes, the muscle memory of code bases are waning.

To keep bugs from slipping through the cracks, we need to address the questions:

- Why do we need to change our attitude towards bugs?

- How do we measure our baselines?

- What needs to change about our workflows?

- How do we make transformation happen?

This talk is a distillation of the lessons learned from the trenches across multiple outages over the years as developer, SRE and an engineering manager.

Instead of looking at how we ship features from left to right, we will start with bugs at the right, and walk backwards along the lifecycle of a bug.

We'll explore debugging workflows, observability gaps, testing limitations, change management processes, and team culture and try to understand how to adapt at this infection point in software engineering.

sessionTranslations.title: Incident Response for Developers
sessionTranslations.description:
8:00 Friday night: you get a call that someone discovered a critical security bug in an application you are responsible for. Congratulations! You are now part of the Incident Response team!

Here you will learn effective ways to collaborate with security teams, management and stakeholders in order to contain the current threat, mitigate the impact of the vulnerability and communicate the scope and risk of the incident. You will also dig into Root Cause Analysis, discover how to document and demonstrate the scope of impact, and learn processes to minimize the potential of future vulnerabilities.

sessionTranslations.title: The 8 Wastes of Software Development
sessionTranslations.description:
Waste in software development isn’t always obvious, but it’s everywhere—hidden in the backlog, baked into processes, and embedded in culture. Borrowing from Lean’s concept of muda—work that consumes resources but adds no customer value—this talk explores how Taiichi Ohno’s classic framework translates into modern software teams.



We’ll break down the 8 Wastes of Software Development: unplanned work, extra features, waiting, unused talent, handoffs, over-planning & incomplete work, repetition, and over-engineering. Each waste will be illustrated with real-world examples—like the dev done feature, the architecture built for scale that never came, and the endless context switching that saps team focus. More importantly, we’ll highlight practical Agile, Lean, and DevOps strategies to eliminate these wastes, so your team can spend less time fighting inefficiency and more time delivering value.

sessionTranslations.title: The Death of the Traditional Sprint: What’s Next for Agile Teams?
sessionTranslations.description: Many orgs are moving away from strict sprints toward continuous delivery or flow-based work. What does it look like to use sprintless models, flow metrics, and modern delivery pipelines? As Agile matures and engineering practices evolve, many high-performing teams are beginning to question the effectiveness of traditional, time-boxed sprints. Are two-week cycles still serving us, or are they holding us back? In this thought-provoking session, we’ll explore the growing movement toward sprintless Agile models, flow-based delivery, and continuous value streams. You'll learn how modern teams are optimizing for outcomes over output using flow metrics, WIP limits, and pull-based planning instead of rigid sprint rituals.

sessionTranslations.title: Learning Computer Science By Building Analog Synthesizers
sessionTranslations.description:
This presentation is an alternate history of your own journey learning computer science. If you started learning all over again, and instead of reading books on C# development or watching videos about Vue.js, you decided to become a developer by building hardware analog synthesizers instead, what would the programming world look like to you?

Imagine that the first computer you used was analog instead of digital, that you learned about abstraction from op amps instead of base classes, and you had to solve problems with an oscilloscope instead of a debugger. You might be very good at understanding computational abstractions!

Building an analog synthesizer from electronic components is a fun way to learn about electrical engineering, but it also holds many lessons about computer science. In this delightfully strange talk, we will build several computational models from the transistors up, learn how to debug from first principles, understand dynamic typing in terms of modular synthesis, and also have a bunch of beeps, blorps, and solder.

sessionTranslations.title: Emotional Intelligence at Work: Choosing the Right Model for Leadership Success
sessionTranslations.description: Which emotional intelligence framework delivers the greatest impact for today's leaders—and does it even matter? While millions are spent on employee soft skills development training, many don't realize they're choosing between fundamentally different approaches that can lead to vastly different outcomes. In this session, we’ll demystify the three dominant emotional intelligence models reshaping workplace performance and discover which approach delivers the greatest impact for specific challenges. You'll explore Mayer-Salovey's Four-Branch Ability Model (focusing on emotional problem-solving skills), Bar-On's EQ-i 2.0 Mixed Model (emphasizing 15 competencies across five domains), and Goleman's Workplace Competency Model (targeting performance-based emotional skills). Recognizing the strengths and blind spots of each framework, you’ll learn when to apply ability-based versus competency-based approaches, and will walk away with a customizable EQ development roadmap and coaching tools to turn everyday workplace challenges into catalyst moments for emotional intelligence growth.

sessionTranslations.title: AI in Performance Testing: Turning Metrics into Meaning
sessionTranslations.description:
Bugs, bottlenecks, slowdowns — performance testing always produces numbers, but numbers alone rarely tell the story. How do you move beyond charts and dashboards to truly communicate what’s happening in your system?



This talk is about using Artificial Intelligence to bridge that gap. By combining performance metrics with AI techniques — including Large Language Models — we can generate clear narratives that explain impact, reveal anomalies, and make complex test results understandable to both engineers and stakeholders.



Based on real-world experience in regulated environments, this session will show you how AI can turn a pile of logs into insight, and a wall of graphs into a story that drives decisions.



Key Takeaways:

-How to apply AI techniques to performance test data to uncover anomalies and user-impacting trends.

-How to communicate performance results more effectively, turning technical metrics into clear, actionable narratives.

-How to integrate AI responsibly into QA pipelines, ensuring clarity and trust in environments where accuracy matters most.

sessionTranslations.title: Learn to paint miniatures
sessionTranslations.description:
Do you play D&D or other role playing games? Miniature games like Warhammer? Or maybe you want to add some pizazz to those plastic tokens that came with a game you love.



Learn the basics of miniature painting, and take home a figure that you painted yourself! You'll learn all the basics, including edge highlighting, drybrushing, and using washes, to take your minis from single color to the star of your game!

sessionTranslations.title: Learn to paint miniatures
sessionTranslations.description:
Do you play D&D or other role playing games? Miniature games like Warhammer? Or maybe you want to add some pizazz to those plastic tokens that came with a game you love.



Learn the basics of miniature painting, and take home a figure that you painted yourself! You'll learn all the basics, including edge highlighting, drybrushing, using washes, and bases; plus a discussion of more advanced topics like airbrushing, zenithal highlighting, and glazes. 



Finally, we'll discuss alternatives to some of the materials that you can DIY at home: instead of buying a pot of technical paint for mud bases, you might have everything you need in your basement!

sessionTranslations.title: Robot Mayhem: Coding Lego EV3 with Python
sessionTranslations.description:
Get ready for some robot mayhem! In this session, you’ll bring Lego EV3 robots to life using Python. First, we’ll make our robots move, then we’ll teach them to react to their surroundings using sensors. Finally, we’ll turn you loose with a challenge — can you make your robot dance, dodge, or explore on its own?

No coding or robotics experience required — just curiosity and a sense of fun. Come ready to code, test, laugh, and unleash a little good-natured robot chaos!

sessionTranslations.title: Everyday SIGINT: Counter-Surveillance with Rayhunter
sessionTranslations.description:
Cell-site simulators (CSS) (“Stingrays”) are devices deployed by law enforcement to pinpoint cell-phone locations and movement. CSS masquerade as legitimate cell-phone towers, tricking phones within a certain radius into connecting to the device rather than the intended cell-tower. CSS remain one of the least transparent, but pervasive surveillance technologies in use, and yes, fraudsters have them too!  Everyday citizens, journalists, and grassroots organizers lack tools to detect or document them, until now. Introducing: Rayhunter—a free, open-source project from the Electronic Frontier Foundation that transforms a $20 mobile hotspot into a portable CSS detector.



This talk explores how Rayhunter democratizes signals intelligence for the layperson. We’ll cover Rayhunter history, setup, and the role it plays in evidence building. Attendees will learn how this low-cost tool empowers individuals to monitor their own cellular environment. By lowering barriers to signals intelligence resources, Rayhunter empowers communities to gather evidence, challenge misuse, and reclaim privacy.

sessionTranslations.title: Building iOS and Apple Watch Health Apps that Shine - AI Powered Development
sessionTranslations.description:
Building health apps for iOS and Apple Watch has never been more accessible—but designing polished experiences that make complex health data meaningful can still be a challenge. What if AI could help us not just analyze user health data, but also accelerate the way we develop and refine our apps?



In this session, we’ll explore how AI tools and agents can support developers in building health-focused apps with iOS and watchOS. We’ll look at how to integrate with HealthKit for activity and biometric data, use AI to generate code scaffolding and UI components, and apply AI models to transform raw sensor streams into clear, engaging visualizations.

sessionTranslations.title: Agents & Arbiters - An Adventurer’s Guide to Multi-Agent Collaboration with LangGraph.js
sessionTranslations.description:
Building interactive systems with conventional coding means trying to anticipate every possible user action and writing the right response. This quickly becomes nigh impossible. You end up lost in a maze of recursion, fragility, and nested if statements. The more interactive you make your system, the more complex your code gets, until debugging feels like being eaten by a grue—you know something's wrong, but you're just fumbling around in the dark.



There's a better way. Instead of scripting every interaction, we can give some of the elements in our system their own intelligence. Multi-agent collaboration lets us create systems where entities can become autonomous agents with their own perspectives and voices. Imagine a text-based adventure game where the brass lantern, the white house, and even the mailbox have something to say when responding to the player. Or consider a help desk system where agents from billing, technical support, and account management each weigh in to determine the best solution for a customer.



In this session, we'll explore multi-agent collaboration through a live demo of a text-based adventure system. You'll meet the orchestration workflow—router, classifier, agents, arbiter, and committer—and discover how LangGraph.js coordinates the chaos when multiple agents want to respond. We'll shine our brass lantern over the code to see how it uses Redis and LangGraph.js to make it all work. Then, we'll explore how this same approach solves real-world problems beyond gaming.



When the adventure's over, you'll understand how to coordinate agents to handle complex interactions and know when this is a good approach. You'll have a working example you can adapt for your own adventures—be they exploring the Great Underground Empire, customer service platforms, or content management systems. And, you'll never look at building interactive systems the same way again.

sessionTranslations.title: Offline-First AI: Building Resilient Tools for a Fragile World
sessionTranslations.description:
No signal? No server? No problem. This talk is about building AI-powered systems that don’t just run in perfect conditions, they thrive in the worst ones.

We’ll explore how to design and deploy offline-first, resilient systems using open-source technologies like Raspberry Pi, mesh networking, and lightweight AI. These tools are part of real-world deployments supporting climate and community resilience, from monitoring extreme heat and air quality to powering local dashboards that run entirely without the internet, hosted on low-power edge devices and accessible over local Wi-Fi or mesh.

If you're a developer, systems engineer, or data tinkerer interested in edge computing, decentralized design, or tech that survives infrastructure failure, this session is for you.

You’ll leave with:

• Design patterns for disconnected delay-tolerant software

• Examples of edge ML deployment using low-power hardware

• A blueprint for building local dashboards that operate in mesh-only environments

• A practical mindset for designing systems that prioritize resilience, autonomy, and access

In a world where cloud-first is the norm and outages are increasingly common, this talk offers a different perspective: how to build software that doesn’t just survive, it endures.

sessionTranslations.title: Building an 8-bit Computer
sessionTranslations.description:
In this hands-on session you'll get to build your very own 8-bit computer from scratch using the legendary 6502 CPU and an Arduino!

  In the first half of the class we'll discuss how the 6502 works internally, and how it can be connected to other components.  We'll then connect the CPU to an Arduino to emulate ROM, and learn how the 6502 executes machine code.

   In the second half, we'll review how assembly code can be turned into machine code and executed by the 6502.  To wrap up, we'll discuss what you need to do to expand your new hobby by using real ROM, RAM, input devices, and display devices.

  Inspired by the popular Ben Eater videos, this session is your chance to get started in the popular hobby of 'homebrew computing'.  All components are provided in the kit available for purchase.



Requirements:

 - A laptop (Mac or Windows) with a USB-A port.

 - To build the computer, you need to purchase a kit from the codemash website. You'll receive the kit at the beginning of the session.

-  You may attend without purchasing a kit pending space limitations. You may also work with someone who has purchased a kit.

sessionTranslations.title: Let's Make Friendship Bracelets!
sessionTranslations.description:
How strong is a single string? What about two strings twisted together? What about three or four or five strings?

In this fun interactive session there will be a live demonstration showing how strong string is using a lever and a scale.

Then everyone will get to make their own friendship bracelets by braiding 5 strings together!  All supplies will be provided.  This session is appropriate for all ages, but young children may need some help from their parents.

sessionTranslations.title: Evolutionary Architecture: Turning a Layered Monolith into a Modular Future
sessionTranslations.description:
Most codebases begin life as simple monoliths, then grow into tangled dependencies that slow development, increase bugs, and frustrate new contributors. Big bang rewrites are risky and rarely succeed. In this session, we show step by step how to evolve a traditional layered monolithic architecture into a modular ports and adapters design using a real 10-year-old open source project as our example.



You will see practical strategies for decoupling features, aligning code boundaries with product teams, and introducing dedicated service modules and database schemas without halting delivery. We walk through common pain points of monoliths, such as tight coupling, long test cycles, and merge conflicts, and demonstrate how incremental refactoring builds a future-proof foundation. Whether you are working on a growing startup project or maintaining a mature enterprise system, you will leave with concrete techniques to modernize your architecture safely and sustainably.

sessionTranslations.title: Climbing the Unclimbed Mountain: Estimation for Software Projects
sessionTranslations.description:
For many reasons, it is challenging to estimate what it will take to finish a software project. One of those reasons is that no one has ever built that project before. How do you deal with the uncertainties inherent in traveling in uncharted territory? 



The first group to climb Mt. Everest had to make plans for climbing into literal uncharted territory. Their planning enabled them to succeed. In this session, we will look at what they did right in their preparation and how you can apply those lessons in your estimates for your next project.

sessionTranslations.title: Java Anti-Patterns: From God Objects to Graceful Code
sessionTranslations.description:
Every Java developer has encountered them - God objects, spaghetti code, and those mysterious magic numbers that seem to appear out of nowhere. These anti-patterns creep in under deadline pressure, inexperienced design choices, or quick fixes that later turn into costly technical debt.



This session is your roadmap to recognizing, taming, and preventing the most common Java anti-patterns. Instead of endlessly patching bugs, you'll learn to build codebases that are robust, maintainable, and even enjoyable to work with.



We'll cover:



Core Anti-Patterns Unpacked: A candid look at God objects, spaghetti code, magic numbers, and their real-world consequences.



Spotting Trouble Early: Practical techniques to detect and address pitfalls before they spread.



Prevention Under Pressure: How to keep code clean - even when deadlines loom.



Lessons from the Wild: Real-world Java examples that will make you laugh, cringe, and (most importantly) learn.



Designing for Elegance: Patterns and strategies to replace bad habits with sustainable, scalable design.



Whether you're starting your Java journey or cleaning up legacy code, you'll leave with actionable practices, new perspectives, and the confidence to write elegant, resilient, and future-proof Java applications.

sessionTranslations.title: Software Craftsmanship for Coding Agents: Taming the Dragon
sessionTranslations.description:
Coding agents like Claude Code and Cursor promise to revolutionize how we build software, but in untrained hands, they're more like dragons—powerful, unpredictable, and likely to burn down your codebase. After building scalable, maintainable production applications with coding agents, I've learned that traditional software craftsmanship principles are not just relevant for AI-assisted development—they're essential for survival.



I'll show you how engineering practices like test-driven development, continuous refactoring, and working in small batches transform unpredictable coding agents into reliable, collaborative partners. Through hands-on coding agent collaboration, we'll build an application from scratch, showing how tight feedback loops and precise task breakdown turn chaotic AI output into production-ready code.



By the end of this session, you'll be able to:



- configure coding agents to enforce your team's coding standards

- use TDD to guide AI code generation and prevent technical debt

- collaborate with agents in small batches for production-ready code

sessionTranslations.title: From 3D Print to Final Product
sessionTranslations.description:
What are the limits of 3D printing? Only your imagination and how much effort you put into print!



For this talk we will go through a number of ways you can transform a 3D print into a quality final product. I will give examples of adding outside elements to prints to make them stronger, heavier, even magnetic. Show the modifications you can make to a print once it’s done. As well as how to design a print that comes off a 3D printer, ready to go!



Even if you don’t have a 3D printer, come in to learn how to think better when it comes to design and creation. You don’t need to stick to one medium to achieve unique goals!

sessionTranslations.title: PKI Unlocked: A No-Math Primer for Builders
sessionTranslations.description: Public Key Infrastructure (PKI) has a reputation for being complicated, but it doesn’t have to be. In this talk, we'll walk together through core cryptography concepts step by step. We’ll start with symmetric encryption and shared keys, then move into asymmetric encryption, hashing, signing, and certificates. From there, we’ll connect the pieces and show how they come together in an actual PKI. Each concept builds on the last to you a clear, practical understanding of how PKI works and how to spot its components in the wild. No math, no crypto proofs, just the essentials developers need.

sessionTranslations.title: CTRL + ALT + REINVENT: Robots Can’t Replace You Unless You Let Them
sessionTranslations.description:
AI isn’t coming for your job—it’s coming for the parts of your job you probably don’t like doing anyway. The real challenge isn’t whether AI will change your work, but how you will change with it. Those who reinvent themselves will thrive, while those who cling to one skill set risk being left behind.



In this session we will explore how to stay relevant and energized in a world where no-code tools, automation, and generative AI are rewriting the rules of work. We will talk about how industries like education, logistics, and media are shifting, and what skills will still matter when machines do the routine tasks. You’ll learn how to spot opportunities instead of threats, how to keep your career from going stale, and how to reinvent yourself so you never get stuck or burned out.



Attendees will leave with a mindset and toolkit for navigating the AI era with confidence, creativity, and a sense of fun. Think of it as a career upgrade, not a replacement plan.

sessionTranslations.title: What Happened to My Snack? The Snack Attacker in a Vacuum
sessionTranslations.description:
What happens to your favorite snack in the vacuum of space? In this fun, live demo, we put marshmallows, balloons, chips, and other everyday items into a vacuum chamber and predict the

results. Will they puff, pop, collapse, or do something totally unexpected? With audience participation and clear explanations, we’ll make invisible air pressure visible and unforgettable.

sessionTranslations.title: Unionization, AI, and You
sessionTranslations.description:
Software engineers have for decades taken for granted that demand for our services will only go up, as will our salaries. We may not have had great job security in any one job, but there was always another one (and a pay raise) around the corner. In our current generative AI world, it is no longer safe to take that for granted.



In this talk, we'll learn about unionization efforts across the tech industry. We'll talk about the realities of unions, both the good and the bad. You'll leave with an understanding of the various steps in forming a union, all the way from recognition to ratification and beyond. And, who knows, maybe you'll get to negotiate a contract with an AI when it replaces the C-suite at your employer.

sessionTranslations.title: The Science Behind Effective Gamification in Mobile Apps
sessionTranslations.description: Let’s level up our knowledge about mobile application development from a scientific perspective–more specifically, gamification! In this talk, you will gain insight into motivation theories, understand the impact of gamification on brain activity, and acquire actionable techniques to enhance your mobile apps through effective gamification. By examining compelling case studies related to this topic, we will discover real-world examples of successful implementations.

sessionTranslations.title: Oligarch‑Free Full‑Stack Blueprint
sessionTranslations.description:
Mega corps have taken control of every aspect of the Internet and social media platforms are walled gardens siphoning off privacy, freedom, and control. It is increasingly difficult to build and run a full-stack application without utilizing big cloud and oligarch infrastructure. This talk will review designing, building and deploying a secure self-hosted, networked, edge, frontend to backend, and backed up application that can be replicated for decentralization and sharing. This is a DevSecOps session focusing on free and open source software and security.

This description was not created using AI. All mistakes are human errorrs.

sessionTranslations.title: Prompts to Patterns - Why Architecture Still Matters When AI Writes the Code
sessionTranslations.description:
Ever watched AI coding agents churn out features in minutes, only to realize your codebase is quietly unraveling into a maintenance nightmare? That is the double-edged sword we are wielding today, and when managers and CEOs just care about outcomes this speed-over-craft mindset becomes a ticking time bomb.



In this talk, I share lessons from a recent engagement where I was tasked with using AI agents to “vibe code” a legacy application into a modern React front end. The goal was not just delivery, but to push the boundaries of the software development lifecycle and uncover the friction points: where humans and machines clash, where prompts fall short, and whether the outcome in time and money would actually be better, worse, or about the same.



Along the way, some patterns began to emerge. Besides a long list of “do not do this” rules, I also found a few practices that held things together, such as reducing duplication, creating clear boundaries in the system, and keeping things simple. These habits acted as anchors in the middle of machine-generated chaos, proving that even when code is written by agents, architecture is still the difference between entropy and endurance. That is why architecture matters now more than ever!

sessionTranslations.title: Building the Ultimate Safety Net with Integration Tests
sessionTranslations.description:
When I started out in development, unit testing was all the rage. We broke functionality into smaller and smaller classes, building mocks as we went. There was a hidden menace here - one refactoring change would break a slew of tests, and I became disillusioned.



This is when I discovered integration tests - a far more effective safety net for ensuring our system works as expected. But building effective integration tests is much more challenging than isolated unit tests.



In this session, I'll break down the common tools used in integration tests for .NET, including the testing package for Microsoft and other extensions such as FastEndpoints. I'll also cover dealing with shared state and infrastructure like databases using TestContainers, and external uncontrollable dependencies.



Finally, I'll share patterns for building effective and maintainable integration tests for a variety of application types, from web apps, to APIs, to messaging endpoints.

sessionTranslations.title: Escaping the Trap of Self-Sabotaging Meetings
sessionTranslations.description:
Meetings are so notorious for draining productivity that historic sabotage manuals listed them as a tactic of choice. The trouble is, modern meetings often fall into the same traps by accident: too many people invited, vague agendas, and decisions that never stay decided. The result isn’t just a wasted hour, but a feedback loop: too many meetings leave no time to prepare, which makes meetings run longer, which forces multitasking, which makes them even less effective.



In this talk, we show how to break those feedback loops before they start. Using lessons lifted from the old sabotage playbook, we’ll contrast common anti-patterns with practical counter-moves: picking the right type of meeting, deciding who actually needs to be there, shaping the environment and logistics, and closing with action and accountability. The aim is simple: meetings that respect time and deliver outcomes. Or, to misquote Arleen Lorrance, be the meeting you want to see happen.



Learning outcomes

* Spot and break meeting feedback loops

* Apply countermeasures to sabotage anti-patterns

* Choose the right meeting type and environment

* Use deliberate prep to respect time and attention

sessionTranslations.title: [CANCELLED] We Shipped an AI Agent. Users Didn’t Care.
sessionTranslations.description:
Shipping still matters. We shipped an AI agent, which is rare right now. Users didn’t care. That isn’t a personal failure, it’s feedback. Value comes from outcomes and what we learn on the way. The real edge is the data we control and the speed we turn experiments into decisions.



In this talk, we treat “not used” and “did not help” as valid, valuable results. We use time-to-truth experiments with explicit kill criteria, so a no-value feature is retired quickly, not defended. We'll compare a product implemented as a simple orchestrated AI workflow, an AI agent, and using a commercial off-the-shelf offering. Building the best products means focusing on what competitors and big tech cannot copy: your data, connections, and unique insight. Even if a feature or app is canceled, the work done can leave durable wins across the platform, from cleaner data contracts to stronger monitoring and evaluation.



Learning outcomes

* Reframe identity: decouple self-worth from features, treat negative results as progress

* Design time-to-truth experiments with clear kill criteria and observability

* Choose buy versus build to avoid racing competitors or tech platform giants

* Leverage proprietary data as a differentiator

sessionTranslations.title: The Lost Art Of Code Reviews
sessionTranslations.description:
Code reviews are a critical aspect of maintaining code quality, but many programmers were never taught how to conduct one. With AI-generated code becoming more common, the ability to evaluate code is more important than ever.



In this session for beginning to intermediate developers, we'll break down what makes a code review effective. You'll learn what to look for (and what to avoid) in general, then move on to more specific examples such as identifying security risks, evaluating REST APIs, and spotting inconsistencies in abstraction and design. We'll examine how to handle team disagreements on code respectfully during review discussions.



We'll look at how to incorporate automation into reviews, such as using static code analysis and linters. We will get practical advice on reviewing AI-generated code.



Attendees will leave with practical techniques for conducting thorough, respectful, and technically sound code reviews, and a checklist for conducting a code review.

sessionTranslations.title: Find Mobile Bugs Faster through ViewModel and API Library Testing
sessionTranslations.description:
Mobile devs are used to testing the JSON or XML that comes across the wire, the standalone logic of their app backend, and the whole app.  But what about the gaps between testing the API output, unit testing your Models and ViewModels with mocks, and testing through the UI?



This session will cover:

* Testing the translation of API data into app Models

* Testing how ViewModels use and cache your app Models

* Testing your API library for fault-tolerance and unusual API responses

sessionTranslations.title: Shift Left on Accessibility: Building Inclusive iOS Apps from Day One
sessionTranslations.description:
When building mobile apps, accessibility often ends up being addressed late in the process, which can make changes harder, slower, and more expensive than they need to be. Even with the best intentions, it’s easy to think of accessibility as a checklist item—something to pass rather than a design principle to embrace. But there’s so much more value in approaching accessibility from the very beginning.



For this talk, I’ll share what I’ve learned by building a small iOS app specifically with accessibility in mind from day one. The app isn’t for work or production—it was created for the purpose of exploring best practices, pitfalls, and practical techniques in an accessibility-first workflow. Through live demos and examples, we’ll see how features like VoiceOver and Dynamic Type can fit naturally into development, how to go beyond the bare minimum, and how accessibility improves usability for all users. Attendees will leave with strategies to integrate accessibility smoothly into their own projects—saving time, reducing technical debt, and creating apps that work better for everyone.

sessionTranslations.title: Build More Responsive and Maintainable Mobile Apps with ReactiveUI
sessionTranslations.description:
Experienced mobile developers know to put as much logic as possible into an app's back-end for maintainability and testability.  But what about logic tied to the user interface like interactivity and navigation?



Instead of using event handlers, delegate callbacks, and a tight coupling between app layers, ReactiveUI allows you to handle user interactions for your front end View through a LINQ-like syntax of subscribing to status changes in your back-end ViewModel.  This makes it easier to test your app by testing your ViewModels independently of their Views with less reliance on UI testing frameworks.

sessionTranslations.title: Azure Fundamentals: Create Your First Cloud Database
sessionTranslations.description:
Are you interested in learning Azure but unsure where to start? This beginner-friendly session will give you a solid foundation to start your Azure journey. You’ll learn the difference between IaaS and PaaS and then follow a step-by-step demo to create your first Azure SQL Database, connect to it from your local SQL Server Management Studio (SSMS), and perform basic operations with tables and data.



What You’ll Learn-



1. The basics of Azure services: IaaS vs. PaaS explained simply.



2. How to create and configure an Azure SQL Database.



3. How to connect securely from your local SSMS.



4. How to create tables and run queries in your new database.



5. Best practices to keep in mind as you start your Azure journey.



This demo-driven session is designed to get you comfortable with Azure quickly, so you’ll leave with the confidence to start building in the cloud.

sessionTranslations.title: Beyond Iron Man: The Reality of Building a Functional Exoskeleton Arm
sessionTranslations.description:
Building an exoskeleton arm isn’t just about strapping motors to metal, it’s about solving dozens of interlocking design challenges, from ergonomics to power to safety. In this talk, I’ll take you through the journey of creating a working robotic arm that can help me lift a 45-pound kettlebell without tearing my own shoulder apart.



You’ll see how the process moved from digital design in Fusion 360, to prototyping on a 3D printer, to machining with CNC tools and precision parts from SendCutSend. Along the way, I’ll dive into the practical hurdles: how to make an exosuit fit the human body, how to choose actuators that are strong but not dangerous, and how to wire, power, and control the system without frying the electronics or myself.



 Whether you’re a maker, engineer, or just curious about what it takes to build real-world wearable robotics, you’ll walk away with a deeper appreciation of both the potential and the pitfalls of exoskeleton design.

sessionTranslations.title: Stop scaling and start tuning
sessionTranslations.description:
When a database is slow, you have two options: burn more money with your cloud provider, or roll up your sleeves and fix it. Many teams click the scale up button first - more RAM and CPU takes 60 seconds and buys them time. But it inevitably comes back worse than before.



My team recently faced the same situation. Scaling up resources had deferred the problem for awhile, but it was time to figure out what was going on. Our system was overwhelming the database in multiple ways: missing indexes, N+1 queries, ORM malfeasance, even a dodgy connection pool.



This talk will walk you through the process we used to fix them: how to decipher telemetry, review query plans, and tune indexes or data access patterns. The issues we uncovered are common in many database applications and you’ll come away with a practical blueprint for resolving them.

sessionTranslations.title: The Simplicity Code: Designing Intelligent Architecture Without the Buzzwords
sessionTranslations.description:
Behind every system that’s easy to scale and evolve is an architecture built on clarity, not complexity. But in a world obsessed with Kubernetes YAMLs, CQRS pipelines, and architecture diagrams that require their own legends, simplicity often gets buried beneath layers of abstraction.



This talk introduces a Simplicity-First approach to intelligent software architecture. We’ll explore how simple, intentional design choices lead to systems that are scalable, resilient, and easier to change—not because they rely on the latest buzzwords, but because they embrace timeless principles: separation of concerns, clean interfaces, evolutionary change, and empathetic design.



We’ll dissect real-world architectures, uncover where complexity quietly creeps in, and walk through how to align technical decisions with business adaptability. Whether you’re modernizing a legacy system or building a cloud-native platform, this session will help you chart a clear path forward.

sessionTranslations.title: [KidzMash] Become a LEGO Master Builder With Teamwork!
sessionTranslations.description: LEGO(R) sets are amazingly fun to build, but who has attempted to build a complete set without looking at the instructions? In this session, the kidz & adults will form teams and try to build one of sixteen different Creator sets without the instructions. Only one person from each team will be able to see the finished picture before the team starts building. That person must share their vision with the team, who will attempt to build the LEGO(R) set as close to the instructions as possible without peeking. The groups will learn different ways to collaborate during the session to build the most accurate Creator LEGO(R) set.

sessionTranslations.title: Modular SPA Web Application: Fast, Secure, and Scalable from MVP to Enterprise
sessionTranslations.description:
This session will demonstrate how modular design enables teams to deliver high-quality web applications faster, safer, and more sustainably. Modular designs can be applied to any web frameworks like Angular, React, Vue, and more.



Modern web applications often face the trade-off between speed, security, and scalability. By leveraging modules, developers can structure applications so that only the required components are loaded at runtime. This approach not only accelerates load times regardless of application size but also strengthens security by preventing unnecessary source files from being downloaded. The result is a streamlined development process that supports rapid MVP releases while maintaining the flexibility to grow into robust enterprise-grade solutions without costly rewrites.

sessionTranslations.title: LLM Lockdown: Defending Against OWASP's Top 10 AI Nightmares
sessionTranslations.description:
In the rapidly evolving world of AI, Large Language Models (LLMs) power innovative applications but also introduce unique security vulnerabilities that can lead to data breaches, ethical lapses, and operational chaos.  This session dives into the security issues identified in the OWASP Top 10 for LLM Applications (2025 edition), providing a fast-paced, actionable overview of the most critical risks facing AI developers today.



We'll explore each of the top 10 vulnerabilities, including real-world examples and mitigation strategies.  The list will cover

how crafted prompt injection inputs can hijack LLMs, risking sensitive information disclosure; how supply chain vulnerabilities in models, dependencies and data poisoning from tampered datasets can threaten security; and how improper output handling and malicious / mis-information attacks can lead to data leakage and unbounded resource consumption and system corruption.



This session is ideal for developers, security professionals, and AI enthusiasts looking to stay ahead in the AI security landscape.

Attendees will leave with a clear roadmap to identify, assess, and mitigate these risks in their own projects,  empowering them to build resilient, secure LLM applications that stand up to emerging threats.

sessionTranslations.title: Full-Stack Flexing with Ruby on Rails
sessionTranslations.description:
Ruby on Rails blasted onto the scene in 2004 with an unapologetic proclamation that Full-Stack applications built with Ruby was what web development needed most. Fast forward over 20 years later and Ruby on Rails 8.0 is here with Full-Stack Flexing to the next level!



Paired with ActiveRecord (Since Ruby on Rails 1.0!) that makes working with a database so easy it's an afterthought, Ruby on Rails 8.0 adds the trifecta of SolidQueue, SolidCache and SolidCable removing the need for Redis altogether. Queuing of jobs, caching to speed up your web application and using pub/sub WebSocket communication straight out of the box.



Add in other Full-Stack building blocks such as Propshaft for your asset pipeline, Kamal 2.0 for easy deployments and a built-in Authentication Generator, Ruby on Rails 8.0 enables you to go from "Hello World to IPO" with the best One-Person Framework out there.



Join this session to learn (or re-learn!) just what an amazing web framework Ruby on Rails 8.0 is and how this technology and community have thrived in the over 20 years it's been together. Find out why the Ruby and Rails community is so passionate about the technology, but even more important are the people that continue to enjoy writing code that makes you smile.

sessionTranslations.title: The Fix is In: Understanding Playwright Fixtures
sessionTranslations.description:
If you have used Playwright for browser automation, you have encountered Playwright Fixtures, one of the core components that sets Playwright apart from other test frameworks. Discover how Fixtures make it easier for you to write test code that is both intuitive and highly reusable.



We'll start by learning what Playwright Fixtures are and how they differ from classic automation patterns like Page Object Model. Next, we'll look at techniques for writing and organizing Fixtures so your tests are easier to read, write, and debug. Finally, we'll explore how Fixtures unlock advanced features like smart cleanup and metadata collection.



Whether you are a Playwright veteran or are considering it for the first time, this session will help you leverage Fixtures to make your test framework fast, reliable, and easy to maintain.

sessionTranslations.title: Assembly Language for People Who Don't Want to Learn Assembly Language
sessionTranslations.description:
Writing assembly language is a lot like driving with a manual transmission.  Very few people want, or need, to use a manual transmission—or write assembly language.  But learning the basics of a skill can help you understand how an automatic transmission works—or how a high-level language works.



This session will teach the basics of assembly language to people who don’t want to know assembly language, but do want to know what it is and to understand what happens to code in a high-level language on its way to being executed by the microprocessor.  



The session starts with a brief overview of digital logic, microprocessors and computer engineering.  Then the difference between machine language and assembly language is explained.  Next is learning a 20 or so instructions in a simple machine language, the machine language of the 6502 microprocessor that was used in the Apple II, Atari and Commodore computers.  



Simple programs will be presented and executed on an online Apple II simulator and a real, live, vintage Apple //c computer.  Finally, students will work in groups to use what they learned then to write, test and debug simple programs and present them to the class.

sessionTranslations.title: Optimizing Complex GenAI Workflows with Event-Driven Multi-Agentic Approach
sessionTranslations.description:
This presentation explores the integration of event-driven data streaming techniques with multi-agentic generative AI workflows, offering a powerful approach to complex system design. By leveraging event streaming, we enable real-time data flow and processing across multiple AI agents, each specializing in distinct tasks such as reflection, tool use, planning, and collaboration.  



We will also discuss event storage criteria, the data models that would be required for Generative AI use cases, as well as how CAP theorem needs to be factored in.



The proposed architecture allows for:



1. Scalability: Easily add or modify agents without disrupting the entire system.

2. Flexibility: Dynamically route tasks and information based on event triggers.

3. Resilience: Distributed processing reduces single points of failure.

4. Efficiency: Parallel processing of tasks by specialized agents.

5. Adaptability: Real-time adjustments to workflow based on streaming data.

sessionTranslations.title: Introduction to Electronics part 1 & 2 (Thursday)
sessionTranslations.description:
Want to get started in electronics but don’t know where to get started? You’ll be shocked how easy it is! Get hands on experience building a few simple circuits and start yer Maker’in!



Kids 10+ welcome with adult supervision. Parts 3 and 4 will cover using Arduino microcontrollers so install Pre-requisites on your laptop for the last section.



Pre-requisites: Arduino IDE (https://www.arduino.cc/en/software)



Additional notes

A paid session is require to get the kit for this class.

sessionTranslations.title: Introduction to Electronics part 3 & 4 (Thursday)
sessionTranslations.description:
Ever want to build something for your house using a micro controller but didn’t know where to start? This is the session for you!



In this session we will use a Arduino Uno, by far not the smallest micro controller, but perfect for getting started by building a proximity sensor circuit. 



We will start with some basics and build the circuit on a bread board. Then we will solder it onto a prototype board.



Additional notes

A paid session is required to get the kit for this class.

sessionTranslations.title: Kidz CAD / 3D-Printing level 2: Intro to 3D Modeling lab (Thursday)
sessionTranslations.description:
This second session is a follow up where we get to make 3D models! 

Children must have a responsible adult present.



We will work with a fully featured CAD application called Rhino3d and walk through the process of building a basic model from geometric shapes. We will explain the XYZ coordinate system, and what the different views are for. We will also spend some time playing with the transform functions. This session is best for kids with basic skills in measurement, elementary-level geometry, and basic computer skills. The session is probably most appropriate for children over 8 but all are welcome based on the child’s capabilities and ability to enjoy. The goal of the session will be to create a cup model we can print for the student.



Less confident or younger kids are welcome to pair up with parents or siblings and just watch the parent/sibling. Kids that complete the kid’s projects without issue are welcome in the adult walk-through labs as they will be making slightly more advanced models that are different.



PLEASE NOTE: We have a fairly large number of printers in the lab so our kids can possibly print items they make in class. If your child completes a model, we will be able to produce a screen render if desired or we will make our best efforts to print at least one model per student, based on demand.

sessionTranslations.title: Adult CAD / 3D-Printing level 1: Intro to CAD and 3D printing (Thursday)
sessionTranslations.description: This session will talk about the exciting world of 3D printing. We will go over exciting trends and happenings in the 3D printing world. We’ll then cover choosing a CAD app and will briefly cover using curated 3D printer object libraries and different CAD apps that might be more appropriate to different types of projects. We will also cover different types of 3D printers as well as the advantages and disadvantages of 3D printing services. After this session you’ll have the starting point on how to make models, where to get them if the model already exists, and where to print them. If you have heard of the exciting world of CAD and 3D printing but have never tried it or would like a basic overview, this session is for you!

sessionTranslations.title: Adult CAD / 3D-Printing level 2: Intro to 3D models in Rhino3d (Thursday)
sessionTranslations.description:
This lab is intended to be a fast-paced technology walk-through of the process of creating a 3D printed object.  We will focus on the process of using CAD to create our model with a NURBS modeler called Rhino3D and will walk through the UI and how Rhino uses basic curves and shapes to create more advanced geometry and create basic models like a goblet, and or a challenge coin. Models can be sent to the 3D printer lab where we will make our best effort to get student models printed!



PLEASE NOTE: High School aged teens or late junior high aged students may also attend adult sessions. Additionally, kids that complete all kid projects in the morning sessions without issue are welcome in this lab as we will be making slightly more advanced models that are different.

sessionTranslations.title: Kidz CAD / 3D-Printing level 1: Intro to CAD/3D-Printing (Thursday)
sessionTranslations.description:
This session is targeted for children. All ages of children are welcome based on their ability to enjoy the content being offered! Children must have a responsible adult present. 



We will talk about and watch videos about the exciting world of 3D printing. We will tour the 3D printer lab and look at the printers as well as models made on them We will also go over basics of how to make models and different types of CAD apps including some that are free or more kid friendly as well as looking at more professional apps as well. We’ll also discuss where to get free models and where to print them. This is the basic overview. Kids should start with this session before using the lab or doing the follow-up modeling course.

sessionTranslations.title: Advanced CAD / 3D-Printing level 3: Making Jewelry (open to Adults and Kidz, Thursday)
sessionTranslations.description:
Want to make something more advanced than the ones you made in our basic CAD overview? We have some additional options to expand model building skills for those who have been through our previous sessions.



We are offering a deeper dive into the process of making jewelry with CAD and 3D printing. We will go over a brief presentation about various ways of making jewelry from CAD models and then we will transition into a more advanced free form Rhino model-building walk-through session to build a pendant that would work for casting. These models can be printed out on our resin printers.



Open to anyone (kids or adults) who have gone through the regular introductory sessions. PLEASE NOTE this session assumes you have taken the basic overview classes OR are reasonably comfortable working in Rhino3D.



After we get some of the models printed, we plan to offer a tech demo of the process of using Delft Clay to make an impression from the 3D models.



PLEASE NOTE: This is a session that is likely to have both kid and adult attendees. If your child has attended the introductory class and is looking for a chance to make something more complex, they are welcome in this class. It is likely best for High School aged teens or late junior high aged students, but any kid that has completed the introductory class without issue and is able to follow a slightly faster paced class may also attend.

sessionTranslations.description:
In this year's learn to solder class we will be making a Robot Alarm Clock!



A ticket is required to get the kit that goes with this session.
