The Angular Renaissance - Key New Features
sessionTranslations.description:
Angular has been stable and capable for a long time, and there were several releases in recent years with only minor improvements. This led many to conclude that the framework was stagnant.



Instead, the reality is that the Angular team was rewriting the internals of the framework to make it more capable in a project called Ivy. Now that Ivy is complete, we are seeing significant changes to improve the developer experience and to add innovative capabilities.



There have been many major improvements in Angular 16 through 21, and we'll cover signals, standalone components, deferrable views, new control flow, and more.



Come to this talk to learn how Angular is leaping forward to make your development life easier.

sessionTranslations.title: Comparing Promises, Observables, and Signals
sessionTranslations.description:
Since JavaScript is single threaded, special techniques are necessary for asynchronous and reactive programming.



Promises were introduced a few years ago to enable asynchronous programming without the dreaded "callback hell". They are a very powerful tool, especially with the async/await syntactic sugar.



But limitations in promises opened the door to observables and their associated operator functions. They are much more powerful than promises overall, but can also be much more confusing.



Signals are yet another approach, one that has gained a lot of attention since Angular adopted them in 2023, but it solves completely different problems.



Now we have three different reactive primitives. Why? What's the difference between them? Why would you choose one over the other? Or will they all have complementary roles in a modern JavaScript/TypeScript application?



Come to this session to get the answers to these questions, and more!

sessionTranslations.title: Dungeons & Debugging: Observability, Evaluation, and Analytics battle AI Complexity
sessionTranslations.description:
Artificial intelligence and machine learning can significantly level up your software capabilities, offering exciting possibilities for applications like interactive storytelling and game mastering in Dungeons and Dragons. However, as any adventurer knows, these powerful technologies can also introduce challenges akin to facing a rogue dragon—unexpected behavior and complex troubleshooting. 



In this talk, we’ll explore how to harness the benefits of AI/ML solutions while maintaining control and minimizing unpredictability. We’ll use observability through OpenTelemetry and Aspire as our magic map to gain insights into the labyrinth of AI orchestration systems using frameworks like Semantic Kernel or Microsoft.Extensions.AI. We'll see how you can define and orchestrate a tapestry of AI systems and evaluate their performance using Semantic Kernel's Process and Agents Frameworks, AI Evaluation and reporting, and plain old data analytics to deliver a high quality solo table top roleplaying game experience.



While the topic is fun, the challenges of optimizing and troubleshooting AI systems is one many teams know all too well. Thankfully, modern advances in evaluation, orchestration, and observability can help stop your application or virtual game master from going chaotic evil on you - or your users.

sessionTranslations.title: Casino (Salons G and B)
Keeping Secrets Out of Your Pipeline
sessionTranslations.description:
Commit your code, push a button, and everything is deployed – the Holy Grail of DevOps. Nobody has to type any commands or passwords to push your app live; everything lives in source control, and it all just works.

Wait a second! My passwords are in source code? How did they get in there? How can I stop it from happening again? And how can I keep credentials out of source code and still make them available to my DevOps pipeline?

We’ll talk about using the open-source TruffleHog tool to find sensitive information in our source code repositories. And how to catch credentials before they are exposed. Finally, we'll talk about what to do when our credentials are leaked.

sessionTranslations.title: [CANCELLED] The No Frills Frontend Migration Survival Guide
sessionTranslations.description:
Migrating a large front-end application, say, moving from AngularJS to React can feel overwhelming at first. It’s easy to think of it as a huge “all-or-nothing” rewrite. But in reality, a gradual migration, done one piece at a time, is not only possible, it's actually the smarter way to go.



In this workshop, we'll walk you through what it really takes to pull off a migration like this without disrupting your team or your product. We’ll look at some of the common challenges you’ll run into like dealing with two different routing systems, keeping state consistent across frameworks, and managing bundle size when both frameworks need to live side by side for a while.



We'll wrap up by getting hands-on with practical strategies that have worked well in real-world projects, including patterns like the Strangler Fig. The goal is to provide a realistic and replicable path forward so you can modernize your app, reduce tech debt, and end up with a cleaner, more maintainable codebase all without grinding your velocity.

sessionTranslations.title: [CANCELLED] Never Trust a Monkey: The Chasm, the Craft, and the Chain of AI-Assisted Code
sessionTranslations.description:
We’re in the midst of another abstraction leap.

Just like compilers, cloud, and containers before it, AI-generated code started with hype, fear, and broken things, and might still end with progress, but only if we build it right.



As we all know by now, LLMs aren't particularly intelligent; they are just monkeys that sometimes output Shakespeare, but with GPUs instead of typewriters. They’ll generate code with confidence, validate it with tests they wrote themselves (if any), celebrate with a lot of emojis, and call it a job well done.



This talk introduces a working model for AI-assisted development that actually holds up under real-world use. It’s built on three ideas:



- The Chasm: the dangerous gap between what we meant and what we asked for.



- The Craft: the human skill to spot when AI gets it “technically right” but still wrong.



- The Chain: the Intent Integrity Chain, a structured flow of prompt → spec → test → code, where each output is validated externally, by humans or deterministic systems, but never by the same model that generated it.



And what we end up with is a blueprint for building production-ready software with AI, without sacrificing trust or intent.



Trust your knowledge.

Trust your tests.

Never trust a monkey.

sessionTranslations.title: Fiber Arts as Programming
sessionTranslations.description:
or how I learned programmers owe it all to fiber



I've been crocheting since 2013 and knitting since 2018, and I had noticed some similarities between the way I approached a project in either fiber arts or programming. What I did not expect to find was a rich history of fiber arts and programming influencing each other. After a little history lesson, we'll start knitting and crocheting - bring a project you're working on or come learn how! If you've got a knack for programming, you might just discover you have a knack for fiber arts too!

sessionTranslations.title: Possessed by Packages: Is Your JavaScript Haunted?
sessionTranslations.description: Is your app behaving strangely? Random network calls? Unexpected behavior? It might not be a bug, it might be possessed. In this spooky session, we’ll explore how malicious packages sneak into your codebase like ghosts through an open portal. You’ll learn how typo-squatting, dependency confusion, and supply chain attacks haunt the JavaScript ecosystem, and how to perform a proper exorcism. We’ll go beyond npm audit and explore tools and habits to stop the haunt before it begins. Leave this talk with a toolkit that wards off evil; digital and otherwise.

sessionTranslations.title: Tuning Azure App Services for Peak Performance
sessionTranslations.description:
Azure App Service remains the best platform for deploying and scaling .NET applications. It's fully managed, loaded with features, and ready for production use without heavy lifting. But just because your app is running doesn't mean it's optimized.



In this session, we'll deploy a .NET 10 application to Azure App Service, establish a performance baseline, and then walk through real-world optimization techniques. You’ll learn how to configure App Service Plans (Windows vs Linux), fine-tune key settings, scale intelligently, and optimize where it makes sense. We'll also explore how to spot and solve performance issues using tools like Application Insights, Azure Metrics, and diagnostic logging.

sessionTranslations.title: Storytelling with Origami
sessionTranslations.description:
In this class, children discover the magic of origami through storytelling. A simple square of paper becomes part of an adventure, with each fold explained as a step in the tale—guiding their hands while the story unfolds before their eyes.



This workshop blends art, imagination, and hands-on learning. Young storytellers practice listening, following directions, and creative thinking as they bring paper characters to life. By the end, every child leaves not only with origami creations to treasure, but with a story they helped fold into being.

sessionTranslations.title: The Wonderful World of Cross-Platform .NET UI Frameworks
sessionTranslations.description:
Developing cross-platform applications is complex. So many options! Of course, when you think of platform-agnostic frameworks you think of .NET, right? RIGHT?!?!? Let me show you how you can develop .NET apps from any dev environment, deploy to any platform, and use your choice of XAML or C# for the UI.



In this session, we will provide a brief overview of the current landscape of .NET xplat UI development, what choices you have, how they compare to one another, and a totally biased deep-dive into one of those options ;)

sessionTranslations.title: Beyond Prompts: Unlocking the Transformational Side of AI
sessionTranslations.description:
Most people treat Generative AI and Large Language Models (LLMs) like a vending machine: insert token, push button, get snack. That’s fine for quick answers, but it misses the real opportunity. What happens when AI is treated not just as a tool, but as a partner or sidekick?



In this talk, we’ll go beyond transactional prompting and explore the transformational shift: how conversations, continuity, and symbolism can unlock better results and reshape the way we work with AI. Expect a mix of laughs, practical takeaways, and stories you’ll be quoting long after the session ends.



By the end, you’ll have a fresh framework for collaborating with AI that makes complex concepts approachable, keeps your creativity at the center, and turns “just tokens” into something much more.



Attendee Takeaways:



1) Code Smarter: Move beyond vending-machine prompting with conversational techniques that yield richer, more reliable results.



2) Connect Deeper: Treat LLMs as collaborators by leveraging continuity, narrative, and symbolism to shape better outcomes.



3) Construct Confidently:  Apply a practical framework for human–AI collaboration that emphasizes judgment, creativity, and guardrails.



4) Communicate Clearly: Use accessible stories and analogies to explain AI concepts to colleagues, teams, and non-technical audiences.

sessionTranslations.title: Launching Rockets
sessionTranslations.description:
It’s not rocket science… oh, but actually, it is!



In this fun and hands-on workshop, you will build and launch safe, small-scale straw rockets propelled by air while exploring aerodynamics, propulsion, and Newton’s Laws. You’ll design, tweak, and test your rocket, aiming for either maximum distance or pinpoint accuracy. Along the way, you’ll see how small design changes can make a big difference in performance, all in a safe and supervised setting.



Will you hit the target first, or will your rocket sail across the room? Either way, you’ll walk away with new skills and a big smile.



Takeaways: Basic physics principles in action, creative problem solving, and an unforgettable launch day experience.

sessionTranslations.title: Is Vector Search Right for Me?
sessionTranslations.description:
Is the term "AI" obfuscating every practical conversation about everything? Can we cut through the noise and ride this wave by understanding, designing, and deploying a new breed of search, fully integrated with your existing data and database? Yes, yes, we can!

This talk will dig into the weeds of vector search. We'll explore both the core math of the technology, as well as the applicability to a wide variety of use cases. We'll differentiate it from preceding search technologies and find how it fits within an overall data retrieval strategy.

I'll discuss some concrete ways this can make your life better but also touch on some pitfalls you might want to watch for.



Attending this session will help you:

1) Understand what Vector Search is and how it works

2) Discover the ways that vector search and "semantic search" help solve problems

3) Learn about some concrete implementations of vector search and how to integrate this architecture into your project

4) Pros and cons of using vector search vs. keyword search

sessionTranslations.title: From Data to Insights in Minutes: Accelerating Business Development with AutoML
sessionTranslations.description:
Are you tired of manually processing large datasets in spreadsheets? 

Do you want to speed up your product development cycle and quickly validate data-driven hypotheses? 

Would you like to leverage machine learning to enhance user experience and foster product innovation, but feel limited by time or coding skills? 

If these challenges resonate with you, you may find this session worthwhile! 



Traditionally, building predictive models for business products requires significant coding expertise and a solid understanding of statistical principles. However, Automated Machine Learning (AutoML) simplifies this process. AutoML enables the rapid creation of robust machine learning models from your data, allowing you to iterate quickly and validate product-related concepts without requiring deep expertise in data science. 



This session will provide a hands-on experience with a powerful, user-friendly, open-source AutoML tool. You will learn how to swiftly prototype and test product hypotheses using your own datasets. Through live demo, we will show how AutoML efficiently processes data, selects the best algorithms for your specific use cases, and presents clear, actionable results. This will empower you to accelerate your product development lifecycle and focus on delivering impactful features. 



Whether you are a backend or frontend developer, a cloud or data professional, or a corporate executive, you will discover how AutoML can transform your data into insights in minutes. Join this session to learn how to harness the power of AutoML tools to enable rapid iteration, validate assumptions, and enhance your product roadmap to deliver impactful solutions faster by closing the gap between development and market.



Key Takeaways: 

- Gain a practical understanding of fundamental machine learning concepts and terminology. 

- Learn about the principles and capabilities of AutoML for rapid prototyping of predictive models. 

- Acquire hands-on skills in using a no-code/low-code AutoML platform to quickly implement and test product hypotheses.



#MachineLearning #ProductManagement #LowCodeML #FastPrototyping #AutoML #DataDrivenProducts

sessionTranslations.title: Life after Tech: Rebuilding your Career in the Post-Tech Economy
sessionTranslations.description:
The tech industry is imploding. More and more of us are competing for fewer and fewer jobs, jobs that are less lucrative, more boring, more stressful, and even more toxic. On top of all of this, jobs that once permitted us to contribute something positive to the world now routinely ask us to ignore our moral compass. It’s time we all take a hard look at the work we are doing, how it’s serving us and our communities, and decide what we’d like to be doing instead.



In this  interactive workshop, a long-time tech worker and certified career coach will guide you through the steps necessary to find your path to a new and rewarding career. We’ll identify our strongest and most transferable skills, uncover what we really hope to get out of our relationship with our work, and then look for new careers in different industries that match our abilities and desires.



You’ll leave with a clear plan of action for your “Life after Tech”

sessionTranslations.title: Your Manager Doesn’t Come with a User Manual (But You Can Totally Write One)
sessionTranslations.description: Let’s face it: managers don’t arrive with step-by-step instructions, but with the right tools, you can figure them out anyway! Success in your role isn’t just about crushing your own goals—it’s about syncing up with your boss like the perfect tech stack. In this session, we’ll dive into the art of “managing up” using empathy, emotional intelligence, and strategic communication. You’ll learn how to decode your manager’s quirks, priorities, and working style (yes, even their 7 a.m. email habit) and craft a working relationship that’s less glitchy and more collaborative. Whether you’re looking to build a better connection or troubleshoot tricky dynamics, this session will leave you with practical strategies to lead with understanding—and make your working partnership a win-win.

sessionTranslations.title: Fresh Hot CSS Features!
sessionTranslations.description:
Do you use a CSS Framework like bootstrap? Or maybe you've been coasting for a few years on your current knowledge of CSS. You've maybe seen something called CSS Grid and wondered what it was... Maybe you have never seen `var()` used before.



Let's discuss the latest newest hottest big features in CSS from the last few years, and get you up to speed on what a browser engine is capable of!



We'll cover the following topics:

- CSS Grid

- Custom Properties

- the `:has()` selector

- CSS Layers

- Container Queries



... And more!

sessionTranslations.title: Dev Proxy: Breaking Your App So You Don’t Have To
sessionTranslations.description:
Ever wonder how your app behaves when the APIs it depends on decide to take a coffee break? Or when they throw a tantrum and start rate-limiting like it's going out of style? Enter Dev Proxy, Microsoft's open-source command-line tool that lets you simulate the chaos of real-world API failures—without actually breaking anything (except maybe your assumptions).



In this session, we’ll explore how Dev Proxy intercepts network requests on your dev machine and lets you:



Mock responses without writing throwaway code,

Simulate errors and throttling with a flick of a config file,

Test your app’s resilience when things go sideways (because they will),

Use plugins to extend functionality—including a custom built implementation!



Whether you're building for Microsoft Graph, REST APIs, or just want to see your app squirm under pressure, Dev Proxy helps you test the untestable. Come for the demos, stay for the debugging drama. Your future self (and your users) will thank you.

sessionTranslations.title: When Feedback Backfires: Strategies for Conversations That Actually Create Change
sessionTranslations.description: You had the best intentions, but somehow your feedback created defensiveness instead of growth; awkwardness instead of improvement. Delivering constructive feedback can spectacularly backfire when it lacks emotional intelligence, especially with defensive, disengaged, or high-performing colleagues who seem impossible to reach. This session reveals why traditional feedback approaches fail and introduces emotionally intelligent strategies enhanced by AI practice tools that help feedback actually land and create positive change. You'll discover how to craft messages that motivate rather than deflate, explore the psychological barriers that trigger defensive reactions, and learn to tailor your approach based on different personality types. Walk away with a complete feedback framework that transforms dreaded performance conversations into trust-building opportunities for growth, complete with coaching tools to build your confidence before high-stakes discussions.

sessionTranslations.title: Yak Shaving for the Apologetic Wanderer
sessionTranslations.description:
We’ve all been there.  You set out to complete a simple task, but before you know it, you're knee-deep in unrelated detours: updating dependencies, fine-tuning a Bash script, or re-configuring your entire toolchain. Congratulations, you’re officially yak shaving.



But is that really a bad thing?



In this talk, we’ll explore the double-edged nature of yak shaving. First, we’ll commiserate over the sheer chaos it can introduce when tiny tangents snowball into lost hours (or days 😅). Then, we’ll flip the script and examine why these mini-quests aren’t always a waste of time. Some of the best optimizations, automation, and deep technical understanding emerge from what originally seemed like distractions.  Finally, we’ll break down a simple framework to help you decide: when should you lean into yak shaving as an investment in the future, and when should you resist the urge and just get the job done?



Whether you’re an engineer, a tech lead, or just someone who’s spent way too long exploring the depths of rabbit holes, this talk will help you tame the yaks before they trample your productivity.

sessionTranslations.title: Architecting for AI: Building Production-Ready Systems with Context, Control, and Automated Testing
sessionTranslations.description:
The explosion of AI capabilities, particularly with Large Language Models (LLMs), has created both incredible opportunities and significant architectural challenges for experienced software professionals. While conversational interfaces capture the headlines, realizing the true potential of AI requires building programmatic systems that can automate complex tasks and drive business value. This talk dives deep into the architectural patterns and techniques needed to move beyond the chatbot demo and build reliable, production-ready AI applications, specifically addressing the pitfalls of general knowledge LLMs.



The key to unlocking LLMs' true potential lies in supplementing their core knowledge with specialized, context-specific information. We’ll explore strategies for enriching the LLM’s understanding before it engages with a prompt – a crucial step in ensuring accurate and reliable responses. This leads us to examine a range of knowledge integration architectures, including RAG, CAG, and KGR. We'll also look at the architecture of Chain-of-Thought (CoT) and how that can improve deep thought problems.  We will also look at architecting different domains of knowledge and function through agentic AI.



Critically, we’ll examine architectures designed to limit both input and output, enabling early detection and mitigation of hallucinations – a key concern for production AI systems. You'll learn how to enforce boundaries and control LLM behavior to ensure predictable and trustworthy results.



Finally, we'll introduce a powerful technique: using AI to generate and validate test use cases, demonstrating a Monte Carlo sampling process for robust testing. This allows for efficient monitoring of progress and rapid identification of regressions, ensuring high-quality AI-powered solutions.  This talk is designed for software architects, developers, and technical leaders seeking to effectively integrate LLMs into their applications. Attendees will gain a practical understanding of how to build scalable, testable, and reliable AI-powered solutions, ready to tackle real-world challenges. You'll leave with actionable strategies focused on delivering AI solutions with verifiable accuracy and controllability.

sessionTranslations.title: Privacy by design (PbD) in DevSecOps
sessionTranslations.description:
Privacy by Design (PbD) in DevSecOps is a proactive approach that integrates privacy considerations into every stage of the software development lifecycle (SDLC), from initial design to deployment and operations. It ensures that privacy is not an afterthought, but a fundamental aspect of how systems and processes are built.

By systematically embedding privacy by design principles into DevSecOps, organizations can build more secure, compliant, and trustworthy applications and systems, ultimately benefiting both the business and its users.

Privacy by Design (PbD) is a fundamental approach to application security that ensures privacy is embedded into the design and architecture of IT systems, business practices, and networked infrastructure from the very beginning, rather than being an afterthought. It shifts the responsibility for data protection away from users and onto the organizations collecting, storing, and sharing the data.

sessionTranslations.title: Caffeinate Your Queries: Brew Up Faster SQL with Tuning
sessionTranslations.description: In this session, embark on an engaging exploration as we unravel the mysteries of query tuning. From deciphering sluggish queries to unleashing their full potential, we will explore advanced techniques for optimizing SQL performance. Discover the art of indexing, rewriting queries for efficiency, leveraging execution plans, and unearthing hidden bottlenecks. Whether you're a seasoned developer or SQL enthusiast, you'll leave armed with the skills to transform your queries from coffee-break slow to lightning-fast.

sessionTranslations.title: Decision Records: Understanding Why Those Decisions Were Made!
sessionTranslations.description: Ever stared at a complex system and thought, "Wait, why was that decision made?!” We’ve all been there – lost in a maze of logic, struggling to track down the root cause of a problem. Decision Records offer a brilliant way to finally unlock that understanding. They’re like having a detailed, searchable log of every decision in your applications – from architectural style to authentication to service discovery and containerization. By capturing these decisions, you build more maintainable, auditable, and, frankly, less frustrating systems. In this session, you will learn how decision records solve problems and will be given ideas of templates that you can implement in your projects today! Let’s ditch the guesswork and start documenting the why – because truly understanding your systems is the key to unlocking its full potential!

sessionTranslations.title: OTel me more! A practical guide for adopting OpenTelemetry
sessionTranslations.description:
Modern software systems rarely follow the classic “frontend → API → database” pattern. Instead, we operate in an increasingly tangled web of services, platforms, and environments—on-prem, in the cloud, or both. In this complex landscape, how can we:



Understand system load in real time?

Detect whether a recent deploy is causing instability?

Catch bottlenecks and errors before customers report them?

Map internal issues directly to customer impact?



This is where observability—and specifically OpenTelemetry—comes in. But adopting observability practices isn’t plug-and-play. There's a learning curve and a lot of choices to navigate.



In this session, we’ll demystify observability through the lens of OpenTelemetry, covering:



What observability really means (and why it matters)

The core signals: logs, metrics, and traces

How to instrument applications using OpenTelemetry SDKs and auto-instrumentation

The OpenTelemetry Collector: how it works, and how to build powerful telemetry pipelines

Real-world use cases showing how to solve tricky production problems using telemetry



All examples will use free and open-source tools, so you’ll leave equipped to experiment and learn without vendor lock-in. By the end of the session, you’ll have a clear picture of the OpenTelemetry ecosystem and practical insights to begin (or improve) your own observability journey.

sessionTranslations.title: Getting Things Done for Technologists
sessionTranslations.description:
If you talk to the most well-known developers, whether they’re people within your organization or internationally recognized experts, you’ll find something in common: they’re productive. Usually, it isn’t just dumb luck. More often than not, they’ve focused on becoming more productive.



There are dozens of methodologies that claim to increase productivity, but there’s a clear winner amongst highly productive software developers: Getting Things Done (GTD). GTD, originally described in productivity guru David Allen’s best seller of the same title, describes a set of behaviors which, when followed regularly, reduce stress and help you become more productive at the same time.



This session looks at how programmers, architects, and technical managers can apply GTD principles to improve the productivity of individuals and the group as a whole. In addition to discussing the core principles of GTD, this session also examines tools which can be used to implement the methodology, as well as similarities to agile software development practices.

sessionTranslations.title: Invisible Technology: Hacking with Infrared
sessionTranslations.description:
Infrared (IR) is literally an invisible technology, but it powers some of the most important everyday gadgets — from TV remotes to motion detectors, robots, and even security systems. In this hands-on Divez, you’ll uncover the hidden world of IR. Using Arduino, you’ll learn how to send and receive IR signals, see them come to life on your computer, and use them to control real devices.



By the end of this workshop, you’ll build two fun projects:



* Universal Remote — copy and replay IR codes to control any IR-enabled device.

* Burglar Alarm — create a security system that sounds an alarm if anyone opens your box of treasures!



Come ready to explore the invisible tech all around you — and leave with the power to command it yourself.

sessionTranslations.title: Beyond the Basics: Designing Web APIs for Long Term Success
sessionTranslations.description:
You've seen all the tutorials and getting-started guides promising a quick path to a web API: pick between REST or GraphQL, choose an API framework, and deploy it to the cloud. But what happens when you need to modify, expand, share, or overhaul that API once it is already live in production?



In this talk, we’ll explore the real-world challenges we faced as our web APIs evolved over several years. We’ll discuss how initial decisions and insufficient planning led us into pitfalls, resulting in tech debt and obstacles when it came time to evolve our APIs.



By addressing design concerns like a well-documented API specification, versioning, Infrastructure as Code (IaC), an API gateway, and enhanced observability, we can avoid future rework and minimize disruption for our customers. Join us to learn strategies for navigating the complexities of evolving APIs and ensuring a smoother path from inception to long-term success.

sessionTranslations.title: You've Probably Never Heard of the Reticulum Network
sessionTranslations.description:
The networks we use every day depend on centralized infrastructure that's vulnerable to censorship, surveillance, and single points of failure. Whether it's disasters, deliberate interference, or plain old downtime, entire populations can, in an instant, be cut off from digital communication—sometimes when they need it most. The heart of the problem is hierarchy—the hierarchical structure of these networks makes them easy to exploit or to simply shut down.



Reticulum is one solution to this problem. It's a cryptography-based networking stack that flattens the hierarchy entirely. It was built for creating resilient, ad hoc, and private networks using almost any communication hardware you can imagine—from LoRa, WiFi, and Ethernet to old school packet radio and serial ports. Whether you're dealing with natural disasters or just want communications that can't be easily disrupted, Reticulum is a powerful tool for building independent, interconnectable networks that work without central points of control.



This talk will break down what Reticulum is and dig into how the protocol works—from its clever addressing tricks to its baked-in encryption. We'll explore the built-in utilities that ship with Reticulum; try out apps like MeshChat, NomadNet, and Sideband for communication; and even show some code and learn how to build apps of our own.



By the end, you'll understand how Reticulum and the applications that run on it work and how to set it all up for yourself. Plus, you'll have the knowledge to grow the network and its capabilities by writing with applications of your own. But most importantly, you'll walk away understanding how to build communication networks that can survive disasters, resist interference, and keep working when traditional infrastructure fails.

sessionTranslations.title: Design to Code for .NET Developers
sessionTranslations.description:
You have the luxury of working with a designer, one who understands the nuances of good User Experience – the Design for your next app looks gorgeous, with a robust design system backing and accessibility features thoughtfully supported with empathy. However, all the design happened in Figma, and now, you have to bring it to life in code – without the right tools, there is a huge chasm rife with possibilities of failure.



Thankfully, .NET developers do have well engineered tools to bring Figma goodness over – with high fidelity that honors the design. Be it for web, native or hybrid .NET apps, Figma Plugins can import design elements and provide developers with a great starting point – how cool is it to get customizable CSS or XAML/C# code directly from Figma designs? Moreover, developers get access to design surfaces to fine tune UI layout, alignment, spacing, behaviors and other design details – perfection needs eye for detail down the last pixel. Let’s explore how .NET developers can translate Figma designs to real apps – one has to care and the right tools can help.

sessionTranslations.title: Who Moved My Mug? Teaching a Raspberry Pi; To Spy ; With Spring-AI
sessionTranslations.description:
What happens when Spring AI meets a Raspberry Pi, a camera, and a pinch of GenAI? You get a smart, little agent that sees, thinks, and reacts in real time. 



In this live demo-packed session, we’ll explore how to bring AI to the edge with a Spring Boot app that connects to Vision APIs and LLMs via Spring AI.



You’ll see real-time:

• A Pi-attached camera that captures ambient scenes

• Spring AI describing the scene in natural language

• Detection of changes and reactions via GenAI



We’ll unpack the architecture, show how to integrate Spring AI with image-based inputs, and cover design choices for edge-to-cloud intelligence. Whether you're into IoT, RAG, LLMs, or just want to build smarter apps with Spring, this talk is your launchpad.

sessionTranslations.title: Layers Are for Lasagna: Embracing Vertical Slice Architecture
sessionTranslations.description:
Is your codebase fragile, where one small change risks breaking something unexpected? That fragility often comes from layered or “lasagna” architectures that scatter logic across controllers, services, repositories, and models. Touching one feature means touching several layers, and every change feels slow and risky. Vertical Slice Architecture takes a different approach.



Instead of organizing by technical layer, it organizes by feature. Each slice contains everything it needs, from input to persistence, and stands largely on its own. This makes features easier to find, easier to understand, and easier to change without worrying about unintended ripple effects. It also gives you the freedom to pick the right implementation for each case, whether that means EF Core, Dapper, or raw SQL.



In this talk, we will explore how to shift from rigid layered designs to feature-oriented slices, and how that shift creates codebases that grow more naturally and stay easier to maintain. Through practical .NET examples, you will see how vertical slicing encourages clarity, flexibility, and confidence when building or refactoring applications. Layers might be fine for lasagna, but your architecture deserves something better.

sessionTranslations.title: Mission-Critical Code: What NASA’s Power of Ten Can Teach Us
sessionTranslations.description:
Ever wonder how NASA writes software that literally can’t afford to fail? Meanwhile, back on Earth, our code is held together with duct tape and //TODO comments. The stakes might be a little lower for most of us—nobody's oxygen supply depends on our latest API deployment (hopefully)—but reliability, maintainability, and simplicity still matter.



Enter NASA’s Power of Ten rules: a set of software engineering principles designed to minimize complexity and maximize reliability. In this talk, we’ll explore these ten commandments of mission-critical coding, from banning recursion (gasp!) to keeping functions tiny and predictable. Along the way, we’ll discuss how these rules apply beyond space exploration—to web apps, enterprise systems, and anywhere else software keeps the lights on.



Whether you're launching rockets or just trying to keep production from crashing at 2 AM, these lessons can help you write code that’s more robust, maintainable, and maybe even astronaut-approved. So strap in, and join us for a journey through the Power of Ten—no space suit required!

sessionTranslations.title: From Idea to iOS: Rapid Prototyping with AI
sessionTranslations.description: Prototyping is often the biggest bottleneck between a great idea and a working app. AI can change that. In this talk, we’ll explore how developers can use AI tools to rapidly generate Swift code, experiment with UI designs, and iterate on concepts in hours instead of days. We’ll walk through real examples of turning rough ideas into functional iOS prototypes, discuss where AI accelerates the process, and highlight pitfalls like unverified code or design mismatches. Attendees will leave with strategies and practical workflows to harness AI as a creative accelerator—helping you move from Figma to your pocket faster than ever.

sessionTranslations.title: The Art of Breaking Things (Before Your Users Do)
sessionTranslations.description:
“Tests prove it works; quality proves it works when life goes wrong.” 

Testers think differently from developers, instead of following the intended path, they explore the detours. This session dives into the tester’s mindset and shows how developers, testers, and mixed teams can benefit from it. Through real-world stories, interactive thought experiments, and lightweight heuristics you can apply immediately, you’ll learn strategies to challenge assumptions, explore edge cases, and uncover risks that automated tests alone can’t catch. It’s the difference between getting a coffee and getting the latte you actually ordered.

Come ready to shift your perspective and discover the art of breaking things, before your users do.

sessionTranslations.title: AI in the Browser: Practical ML with JavaScript
sessionTranslations.description: Getting started with AI shouldn’t require a new toolchain. In this session, you’ll see how modern JavaScript lets you run real ML workloads in the browser—no servers, minimal setup. We’ll load a vision model with TensorFlow.js, use a MediaPipe task for real-time perception, and run a small transformer locally with Transformers.js. Along the way we’ll cover when browser-side AI shines (privacy, latency, portability) and when you should fall back to a service. You’ll leave with copy-pasteable patterns for model loading, batching, performance (WebGPU/WebGL), and graceful degradation on lower-end devices. No deep math required—just JS, a browser, and a few well-chosen libraries.

sessionTranslations.title: Digging into the Matrix: Practicing Code Archaeology
sessionTranslations.description:
Most of the code that exists in the world is code you didn’t write, and so most of the code you work with is also code you didn’t write, even if you’re not working with a legacy system. But when we don’t understand that code, we can all too often dismiss, disparage, or even simply delete it - and that’s a mistake! 



Almost all the code we interact with was written by other humans, and they wrote the code that way for a reason. If we take the time to understand the context and the story behind a piece of code, we can infer a lot about what those humans meant to achieve, what their culture was like, and what they valued… in other words, we need to become an archaeologist!



Let’s work to build a better understanding of the code we didn’t write, and of who wrote it and why. Using the tools of psychology you can learn what’s happening to your brain when you’re reading someone else’s code, and then learn how you can make understanding it take less cognitive effort. Using the tools of archaeology you can learn how to use your development environment to find the real stories of the people that wrote it, and how that story can protect you from making the same mistakes they did. The ability to read and examine others’ code is essential - you can’t change or improve software without understanding what it already does, so come learn how to do it with skill and compassion!

sessionTranslations.title: The Premortem: The Art of Killing a Project to Ensure Its Success
sessionTranslations.description:
Many projects fail, often due to risks that could have been foreseen. In this session, we'll demonstrate how a premortem analysis can help you kill a project's risks before they can kill the project itself.



We will use a hands-on approach, imagining a project has failed and working backward from that hypothetical disaster to identify the root causes. We’ll uncover blind spots and proactively address them, turning potential failures into actionable plans.



The result? A dynamic, intelligent way to approach project planning, making your teams more resilient and ready for success.

sessionTranslations.title: Thinking Architecturally
sessionTranslations.description:
Rich Hickey once said programmers know the benefits of everything and the trade offs of nothing...an approach that can lead a project down a path of frustrated developers and unhappy customers. As architects though, we must consider the trade offs of every new library, language, pattern or approach and quickly make decisions often with incomplete information. How should we think about the inevitable technology choices we have to make on a project? How do we balance competing agendas? How do we keep our team happy and excited without chasing every new thing that someone finds on the inner webs?



As architects it is our responsibility to effectively guide our teams on the technology journey. In this talk I will outline the importance of trade offs, how we can analyze new technologies and how we can effectively capture the inevitable architectural decisions we will make. I will also explore the value of fitness functions as a way of ensuring the decisions we make are actually reflected in the code base.

sessionTranslations.title: Managing Up, Sideways, and All Around: Surviving the Human Side of Tech
sessionTranslations.description:
Writing code is often the easy part. The real challenge comes in navigating the people side of software development. Whether it is keeping your manager confident, helping a client feel informed, or smoothing things over with your teammates, success in tech depends as much on communication and trust as it does on technical skill.



In this session we will explore the art of managing in every direction. You will learn how to manage up so your manager never has to chase you for updates, how to manage clients so they feel guided without endless status calls, and how to manage sideways so collaboration with peers stays productive instead of combative. We will also look at common pitfalls, like overloading stakeholders with detail, assuming silence means agreement, or letting peer conflicts go unresolved.



Attendees will leave with practical techniques for building trust, sharing the right information at the right time, and making the human side of engineering feel less like a minefield. Because let’s be real: Git conflicts are nothing compared to people conflicts.

sessionTranslations.title: Going Vertical: Signals from the Sky
sessionTranslations.description: Last year, the CodeMash balloon launch flew all the way to Alunda, Sweden. In this session, we’ll explore Raspberry Pi PICO and high altitude balloons that reach near space at over 100,000 feet. You’ll see how Pi PICO boards and recycled radiosondes can be programmed to send telemetry that can be received and decoded by SDRs, but no special equipment is required. The data from these flying devices is uploaded to the internet, making it possible to follow and analyze balloon flights from anywhere. We’ll also show how Docker works as a portable compiler to build and run the tracking code. Weather permitting, we will launch a balloon that participants can track live during the conference.

sessionTranslations.title: Command your IoT Projects from the Terminal
sessionTranslations.description: This session will cover all of the main development platforms like Arduino, Circuit/Micro Python, Pico C++ and ESP-IDF when targeting a wide array of chipsets and boards including ATiny, ATmega, ATsamd, RP2040/2350, nRF52xxx and ESP32 board variants.  Focusing on the core building blocks of chip based development, this overview will include tools, tips and techniques for making command line development both locally and over ssh as painless and as easy as using their graphical IDE counterparts.  From debugging to flashing boot loaders, to updating helpful libraries.  When all is said and done, you will better understand what the underpinnings of your favorite IDEs have been doing under the hood.

sessionTranslations.title: Setting Your Tests Up to Fail
sessionTranslations.description:
It's a fact of life that we often have to write automated tests for features that have defects, or that interact with 3rd party APIs that aren't returning the right responses, or for items that we know aren't working right.  When the team has decided that the behavior isn't going to be fixed, what's an automation engineer to do?  Let the tests fail?  Not write them? Champion harder for the defects?



I suggest writing your tests to pass and setting them up to fail.



By creating tests that pass on the current expected behavior (the defect), we are in a perfect position to tell when the defect is resolved, or the api is returning the correct information, or any of the other error cases we may be encountering.  This prevents failure fatigue (from seeing a test 'always fail), while still providing meaningful, actionable information out of our test suite.



We will discuss several cases that I've experienced that this method has worked for as well as how to keep the rest of the team informed through TODOs, Jira stories, and documentation.  And--of course!--what to do when your test finally fails.

sessionTranslations.title: From Pixels to Plastic: Your First 3D Printed Model
sessionTranslations.description:
Ever wanted to turn a digital design into something you can hold in your hands? In this session, you’ll learn the full workflow of 3D printing: from designing a model in free 3D software to slicing it for a printer and producing the physical parts. We’ll also explore different approaches to modeling, including parametric for precise parts, mesh for organic shapes, curves/NURBS for smooth surfaces, and Booleans for combining or cutting forms.



To finish, you’ll assemble the printed pieces into a completed interactive model you can take home! Attendees will leave with practical experience in both 3D modeling and printing, and armed the knowledge of how to choose the right modeling approach for their own future projects.

sessionTranslations.title: When Your Identity Gets Lost in IoT Technology
sessionTranslations.description: Non-native English speakers often face frustration when technology, from voice recognition systems to everyday apps, fails to understand their accents or dialects. In this talk, the speaker explores how these technologies can unintentionally marginalize immigrant communities and overlook diverse identities. The session will cover the broader challenges of accessibility for non-native speakers, the impact of historical events on languages and data collection, and how a simple solution was created to help a family navigate technology. Learn how we can create a more inclusive, accessible world for all users, no matter their background.

sessionTranslations.title: Deceptive UX Patterns: Exposing Manipulative Design and Building Ethical Experiences
sessionTranslations.description:
"Congratulations! You are the 1,000,000th visitor to our website. Click here to redeem your prize! Just provide your date of birth and phone number to get started." Sound familiar? These are examples of manipulative UX patterns that subtly steer users into unintended decisions - spending more, compromising privacy, or making choices they didn't intend. From the frustration of a "Roach Motel" to the intrusion of "Privacy Zuckering," these tactics exploit cognitive biases and unethical design practices.



In this fast-paced session, you'll learn to identify and understand these deceptive patterns and the psychology behind them. We'll cover real-world examples from websites and apps you use every day, including techniques like "Bait and Switch," "Trick Questions," and "Confirm-shaming." You'll gain actionable strategies to architect for digital well-being, prioritize inclusive and accessible design, and make ethical decisions that foster trust with users.



Whether you're a designer, developer, product manager, or concerned end-user, you'll leave empowered to spot manipulative patterns, advocate for ethical design in your organization, and build products that truly serve users' needs. Join us to explore the "UX Hall of Shame" and discover how to protect your users, your product, and your integrity.

sessionTranslations.title: Spies, Secret Messages, the Internet, and You!
sessionTranslations.description:
Have you ever wanted to make a secret message? Unreadable without the key?



This session will show you ways that you can create your own secret messages! Starting with some cyphers from history up to ones used on the internet, you'll learn how people protected secrets yesterday and today.



You'll also learn a little bit about how secret messages can be broken and why it is important to have good passwords to protect your secrets on the internet.



Then you'll practice creating your own secret messages using a variety of methods! 



(Supplies for making your own messages will be provided; Secret Decoder Ring not included)

sessionTranslations.title: From Power to Supply Chains: Sustainability is Security
sessionTranslations.description:
Technology is moving fast, and so are the environmental challenges we face. Security sits right in the middle of these pressures. It’s no longer just about defending systems—our choices around power, hardware, and supply chains also shape how secure those systems really are.



In this talk, I’ll explore why sustainability belongs in the security conversation. We’ll look at practical steps—like energy-efficient tools, leaner software, greener data centers, and responsible hardware lifecycles—that cut waste and costs while strengthening defenses. Just as importantly, we’ll examine how unstable supply chains, poor sourcing, or unreliable power can become security risks in themselves.



We’ll also connect this to risk and compliance: how building sustainability into security reduces exposure, steadies supply chains, and keeps organizations ahead of changing expectations. With real-world examples, you’ll walk away with a clear sense of how sustainability and security reinforce each other, and how to apply that thinking in your own work.

sessionTranslations.title: One String, Many Prompts: A Hands-On Workshop in AI Code Generation
sessionTranslations.description: What if one tiny JSON record could unlock an entire pipeline of working code? In this fast-paced, hands-on 2-hour workshop, we’ll use a single JSON string to generate cross-platform solutions with AI — spanning microcontrollers, APIs, and databases. Attendees won’t just see AI-generated code; they’ll actively craft prompts, refine them, and evaluate the results in real time. Along the way, we’ll reveal a powerful feedback loop: every prompt is captured, then fed back into AI for critique, showing how better organization and phrasing yield stronger outcomes. Whether you care about IoT tinkering, backend APIs, or data pipelines, you’ll leave with practical techniques for writing and refining prompts that turn AI into a productive coding partner.  Whether you’re into IoT tinkering, backend APIs, or data engineering, this fast-paced session will show you how AI can accelerate development across the stack — starting from one simple string. { "recorded" : 1756655999, "location" : "den", "sensor" : "bmp280", "measurement" : "temperature", "units" : "C", "value" : 22.3 }

sessionTranslations.title: Optical Illusion Confusion!
sessionTranslations.description: Have you ever seen something that looks like its moving but its not? What about a 2d shape that looks like 3d? You've just found an Optical Illusion. Lets dive into the world of Optical Illusions to see what makes them so tricky and even making our own!

sessionTranslations.title: Ditch the Compliment Sandwich: Give Feedback That Works
sessionTranslations.description:
Giving feedback is awkward, stressful, and necessary. If you’re a team lead or engineering manager, you can’t let the fear of a tough conversation prevent you from building your people up.



While the “compliment sandwich” (praise-criticism-praise) might ease the awkwardness, it doesn't get results. In this talk you will learn an alternative 4-part technique that has consistently reduced my anxiety and helped me give effective guidance to multiple teams. We’ll break down the model in depth and practice with real-world examples, including what to do with conversations that go sideways.

sessionTranslations.title: Rethinking React Styling for the RSC Era
sessionTranslations.description:
React’s styling landscape is evolving fast. With Server Components, Tailwind v4, and the next era of CSS standards, our old habits need an upgrade. In this talk, we’ll put CSS Modules, Tailwind CSS, and CSS-in-JS to the test against real-world demands like server-side rendering, streaming UI, scalable theming, and runtime performance. 



You’ll learn how styling choices impact payload size, async behavior, and design system consistency at scale. We’ll break down hidden trade-offs between utility-first, scoped CSS, and runtime CSS-in-JS approaches. Expect a practical decision-making framework you can apply immediately to your projects, one that balances developer experience with production performance. You’ll leave with a modern roadmap for building React apps that are styled to last.

sessionTranslations.title: Model Context Protocol: A Systems Integration Perspective
sessionTranslations.description:
Model Context Protocol (MCP) is everywhere these days. It’s often presented as a revolutionary new paradigm that’s going to replace everything, but at its core, it's simply another interface for fetching data and performing remote actions—like REST or RPC. This session reframes MCP through a systems integration lens, demonstrating how to integrate it with your existing systems rather than replacing them entirely.



We'll explore practical integration patterns: how MCP servers can wrap existing REST endpoints, database connections, and internal services; integrating MCP authentication with your current OAuth2/OIDC infrastructure; and designing MCP interfaces that complement rather than duplicate your existing API ecosystem by providing the structured metadata and discoverability that LLMs need to effectively interact with your systems.We'll explore practical integration patterns: how MCP servers can wrap existing REST endpoints, database connections, and internal services; integrating MCP authentication with your current OAuth2/OIDC infrastructure; and designing MCP interfaces that complement rather than duplicate your existing API ecosystem.



This session is designed for teams who want to cut through the hype and approach MCP pragmatically. You'll leave understanding that MCP adoption doesn't require vast new technology investments or architectural overhauls—it's fundamentally an integration challenge that can be solved using familiar patterns and existing infrastructure.

sessionTranslations.title: 🚗 Seeing Roads Differently: Inside Comma.ai’s Open-Source ADAS
sessionTranslations.description:
What if you could retrofit your car with driver-assist capabilities once reserved for luxury vehicles? Comma.ai’s openpilot project has made that vision real: an open-source advanced driver-assistance system (ADAS) that anyone can experiment with. By pairing off-the-shelf hardware with neural networks running at the edge, Comma.ai has created a platform where hackers, engineers, and researchers can push the boundaries of vehicle automation outside of the closed OEM ecosystem.



In this session, we’ll explore how openpilot works under the hood. We’ll walk through the core components — from the Comma 3X hardware with its camera and sensors, to the CAN bus integration that allows reading and sending steering and throttle commands, to the perception and planning loops that keep the car centered and adaptive on highways. We’ll also highlight the critical role of driver monitoring, showing how computer vision ensures the human remains engaged and in control.



We’ll then look at the open-source ecosystem that powers innovation. The openpilot community trains and refines models, crowdsources driving data, and reverse-engineers vehicle signals to expand compatibility. This collaborative approach has created one of the most advanced community-driven ADAS platforms available today, and it opens the door for research into new safety and autonomy features that OEMs may not prioritize.



Finally, we’ll dive into what’s next: training openpilot for advanced behaviors such as recognizing and reacting to stop signs, or detecting an incapacitated driver. We’ll cover what it takes to collect and label the right data, the challenges of training models for real-time edge deployment, and how these features integrate into the planning stack to ensure safety. We’ll close with the ethical and regulatory questions that arise when extending autonomy in open-source form — and how developers can contribute responsibly to making cars smarter, safer, and more accessible.

sessionTranslations.title: Secure Your Web Apps Against OWASP Top 10 Threats
sessionTranslations.description:
The web remains a dangerous place.



Securing your web APIs and applications has never been more important, or more difficult in the face of sophisticated threats and bad actors. Fortunately, the Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) exists to at least identify and share mitigations for the most popular attacks.



In this session, we'll learn about the OWASP Top 10 threats for 2025, released earlier this year. We'll demonstrate each threat and show how we can design our applications to better withstand them. You'll leave this session with concrete ways to improve your app's security and many resources for learning more about how to write secure web applications.

sessionTranslations.title: Agents That Build Themselves: How to Outlive the Hackathon
sessionTranslations.description:
Internal tools often die young. They’re built fast, then fade when the novelty wears off. We set out to do something different: start with a real business problem, build responsibly, and learn what it takes to make an internal AI agent viable. Along the way, we pushed ourselves further: every line of code came from an AI model.



The journey started with staffing. As the company grew, managers lost track of who knew what and who was available. The agent bridged structured data with soft knowledge, surfacing options without replacing human judgment. From there, it stretched into other domains: CRM queries, analytics over a data lake, and lightweight business intelligence.



Keeping the experiment honest meant instrumenting everything. We used dashboards to track cost and usage, traces to debug the agent’s thought process, and LLM-as-judge evals to measure and score the output. Human approval gates gave us confidence where the risks were higher.



This talk shares the case study- here we started, what we built, and what we learned- so you can apply the same lessons to your own agents before they get stuck in the prototype graveyard.



Learning outcomes:

- Evaluate where agents provide value, and where they won’t

- Design agents that bridge messy data, planning, and human judgment

- Test agent behavior with quantitative data and LLM-as-judge evaluation frameworks

- Combine instrumentation, governance, and data engineering into sustainable AI systems

sessionTranslations.title: Making Reality Virtual: Simulating Experiences with VR Prototyping
sessionTranslations.description: Take the Red Pill, and let's dive into the mind-bending Matrix that is Virtual Reality prototyping. Not just for gaming (though that's cool too), a new dimension of experience simulation is now open to designers of software as well as physical products, to observe customer interaction and gather feedback without ever having to create a real product. In this session, explore the hardware and software tools, and the varying techniques we can leverage to put potential customers into a world unlike anything they're used to, or even places they're already familiar with. Learn how to observe their interactions with those experiences, empathize with them in specific contexts and better understand their behaviors. Discover how we can help solve problems or create new engaging content that fits their needs with this new virtual realm. Finally, learn how to validate physical product ideas, not just software and games. Walk away with everything you need to get started prototyping VR experiences (except the hardware itself).

You will also learn how to make other types of sunshine prints at home with other processes, none of which require a darkroom or a printer.

sessionTranslations.description:
This session is targeted for children. All ages of children are welcome based on their ability to enjoy the content being offered! Children must have a responsible adult present. 



We will talk about and watch videos about the exciting world of 3D printing. We will tour the 3D printer lab and look at the printers as well as models made on them We will also go over basics of how to make models and different types of CAD apps including some that are free or more kid friendly as well as looking at more professional apps as well. sessionTranslations.title: Kidz CAD / 3D-Printing level 2: Intro to 3D Modeling lab (Friday)
sessionTranslations.description:
This second session is a follow up where we get to make 3D models! 

Children must have a responsible adult present.



We will work with a fully featured CAD application called Rhino3d and walk through the process of building a basic model from geometric shapes. We will explain the XYZ coordinate system, and what the different views are for. We will also spend some time playing with the transform functions. This session is best for kids with basic skills in measurement, elementary-level geometry, and basic computer skills. The session is probably most appropriate for children over 8 but all are welcome based on the child’s capabilities and ability to enjoy. The goal of the session will be to create a cup model we can print for the student.



Less confident or younger kids are welcome to pair up with parents or siblings and just watch the parent/sibling. Kids that complete the kid’s projects without issue are welcome in the adult walk-through labs as they will be making slightly more advanced models that are different.



PLEASE NOTE: We have a fairly large number of printers in the lab so our kids can possibly print items they make in class. If your child completes a model, we will be able to produce a screen render if desired or we will make our best efforts to print at least one model per student, based on demand.

sessionTranslations.title: Fundamentals of Software Engineering in the age of AI
sessionTranslations.description:
Agentic IDEs and AI chat interfaces are transforming development workflows, leading some to proclaim the end of software engineering. Is it time for you to explore other careers? Not so fast, the rumors of our demise are greatly exaggerated. While these tools can generate boilerplate and enable "vibe coding," working code and engineered systems are worlds apart.


In this session, you'll discover why the fundamentals of software engineering are vital, not replaceable, in the age of AI. We'll explore the journey from programmer to engineer, covering core skills like reading and writing code effectively, technical practices including software modeling and working with existing codebases, and essential application development concepts from UI design to software architecture.


You'll learn how mastering soft skills to career management become even more critical when the task of writing boilerplate code is common amongst your peers. Based on our book "Fundamentals of Software Engineering," this talk will equip you with a roadmap for thriving in an AI-augmented development landscape and understanding what it truly means to evolve from writing code to being a software engineer.

sessionTranslations.title: The Developer Skill Tree: Growing Beyond the Code
sessionTranslations.description:
Being great at coding gets you in the room, but soft skills determine how far you grow once you’re there. In fast-paced, collaborative environments, developers are expected to write excellent code and navigate communication, feedback, conflict, and change. But we rarely get formal training on how to do that well.


In this talk, we’ll explore the most underrated branches of the developer skill tree, empathy, communication, and adaptability, and how strengthening them can level up your impact, your team dynamics, and your career. You’ll walk away with practical strategies for having better 1:1s, asking smarter questions, staying flexible when requirements shift, and building a reputation as someone who makes teams better, not just codebases.


Whether you're mentoring, contributing to open source, or navigating your next role, this talk will give you the tools to grow in the places your IDE can’t see.
